23... Nc4 { A typical Ruy Lopez/Najdorf structure, where Black had to give up the defender of the dark squares around the king. } 24. b3 Nb6 25. f4! { The most precise way to attack! Now White opens up the f-file for his rook. Black has to take, otherwise f4-f5 comes even with greater effect. } { [%cal Rf4f5] } 25... exf4 26. Qxf4 Rd7 { Black gets out of the pin. } 27. Qf2 { Nf3 directly with the same idea is also fine. } { [%cal Gf2b6] } (27. Nf3 { is strong as well. }) 27... Nh7 28. Bf4 Nc8 29. Nf3 { [%cal Gf3d4] } 29... Kg8 30. Qg3 { [%cal Gg3g8,Gf3d4,Gd4f5] } 30... Rde7 31. Nd4 Qf6 32. Nf5 Re6 33. Rf1! { At last White will use f-file and e4-pawn is indirectly protected. } 33... h4 (33... Bxe4 34. Bxe4 (34. Nh6+ Kg7 35. Bxe4 Rxe4 36. Bd2 { [%cal Gf1f8] }) 34... Rxe4 35. Nh6+ Kg7 36. Bd2 Qe5 37. Rxf7+ Kh8 38. Qxg6) 34. Qg4! Qxc3 35. Bd2 Qb2 36. Nh6+ Kh8 37. Nxf7+ Kg7 38. Nd8 R6e7 39. Nxb7 Rxb7 40. Be3 Nf6 41. Qxh4 { 1-0 White wins. } 1-0


