{ Yet another bullet game in the November 2025 edition of 'Game Of The Month'! The main advantage of annotating a bullet game is that the analysis doesn't need to be too deep, as players primarily rely on their intuition. }
1. e4 { [%clk 0:01:00] } 1... g6 { Black can safely premove next move, as 2.♗h6 can not be played to punish this setup. 😉 } { [%clk 0:01:00] } 2. Nc3 { This is a typical bullet chess move as well. } { [%clk 0:01:00] } 2... Bg7 { [%clk 0:01:00] } 3. d4 { [%clk 0:00:59] } 3... Nf6?! { Another premove that can be punished by being pushed back. } { [%clk 0:01:00] } 4. Nf3 { [%clk 0:00:59] } (4. e5 { I thought if this were a blitz game, we would likely see this move; however there are two games in the Masters Database and White chose not to play this there either. } 4... Ng8 5. Bf4 d6 6. Nf3 (6. Qe2 $16 { White will castle long and launch a pawn storm on the kingside. } { [%cal Ge1c1] }) 6... dxe5 7. Nxe5 Nf6 { 2 tempi up compared to the game continuation! }) 4... d6 { [%clk 0:01:00] } (4... d5 { Since White did not play 4.e5, this is a logical alternative. A theoretical discussion might begin after: } 5. e5 Ne4 6. Nxe4 (6. Bd3 Nxc3 7. bxc3 c5 $132) 6... dxe4 7. Ng5 c5 8. Bc4 O-O $10) 5. e5 { As far as I know, this is generally not a good idea here. } { [%clk 0:00:58] } 5... dxe5 { [%clk 0:00:58] } 6. Nxe5 { This position can arise after the moves: 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 ♕xd5 3. ♘c3 ♕d8 4. d4 ♘f6 5. ♘f3 g6 6. ♘e5 ♗g7- though it would be White's turn to move. } { [%clk 0:00:58] } (6. dxe5? Qxd1+ 7. Nxd1 Ng4 8. Bf4 Nc6 9. Bb5 Bd7 $15 { [%cal Gc6e5] }) 6... Nfd7! { A clever retreat to open the dark squared bishop's diagonal with tempo, preparing ...c5 or ...e5. } { [%clk 0:00:58] } 7. Nf3! { It is better to avoid the exchange, as White enjoys more space for their pieces. } { [%clk 0:00:56] } 7... O-O { [%clk 0:00:57] } 8. Be3 { [%csl Ge1][%cal Gd1d2,Re1c1] [%clk 0:00:56] } 8... c6 { Black decides to attack with ...b5-b4. Since White has no similar "hook" on the queenside, this plan proves to be rather slow. } { [%clk 0:00:55] } (8... c5 { A very typical thrust to use the power of♗g7. } 9. d5 Qb6 $132 { It is not clear if White would go for castling long in this situation as well. }) 9. Qd2 { [%cal Ge3h6] [%clk 0:00:55] } 9... b5 { [%clk 0:00:53] } 10. Bh6 { [%clk 0:00:55] } 10... Bxh6 { [%clk 0:00:52] } (10... Nf6 { Declining the queen invitation might be safer; but in a bullet game, the more complications, the better. Black might use white's queen to counterattack with ...♘g4. }) 11. Qxh6 { [%clk 0:00:55] } 11... Nf6 { [%clk 0:00:52] } 12. O-O-O { and now White is ready to attack black's king utilizing the hook on the g6-square. Stockfish points out } { [%clk 0:00:52] } (12. Bd3 { is a useful preparatory move against } 12... b4 13. Ne4 $40 { and White can still castle short if necessary. } { [%cal Gf3g5] }) 12... a5? { Black has less margin for error, as their king is more exposed. A single misstep here is fatal! } { [%clk 0:00:51] } (12... b4! { A very important move not to attack but to dislodge White's knight which will have a deadly effect on White's kingside attack as we shall see. } 13. Ne2 Ng4 { [%cal Gg4f2,Gg4h6] } 14. Qh4 a5 $132 { Now this is an acceptable version as black's king would feel safer on ...g7 if necessary. }) 13. Ng5! { Black's kingside is now frozen! } { [%cal Gc3e4,Gh2h4,Gh4h5] [%clk 0:00:51] } 13... Nbd7 { [%clk 0:00:49] } 14. h4 { White's attack now appears unstoppable. } { [%clk 0:00:49] } 14... b4 { [%clk 0:00:48] } (14... Re8 { [%cal Gd7f8] } 15. h5 Nf8 16. hxg6 fxg6 { is Stockfish's try to defend for Black, but after } 17. d5! { White would be determined to remove black's knight on f6 and ♖d1 is ready to join the attack. }) 15. Nce4 { [%clk 0:00:46] } 15... Ba6 { [%clk 0:00:47] } 16. h5 { [%clk 0:00:44] } 16... Bxf1 { [%clk 0:00:45] } 17. Rdxf1 { [%clk 0:00:40] } (17. hxg6 { would be winning similar to the game. } { [%csl Gh7][%cal Gg5h7] } 17... fxg6 18. Nxh7 $18 (18. Ne6 $18)) 17... b3 { [%clk 0:00:44] } 18. hxg6! { The flashy finish! Black's counterplay arrives too late. White is still much faster after } { [%clk 0:00:38] } (18. axb3 a4 19. hxg6 $18) 18... bxa2 { [%clk 0:00:43] } 19. Nxh7!! { This is the point! Black is allowed to promote with check but it is to no avail. } { [%clk 0:00:22] } 19... a1=Q+ { [%clk 0:00:40] } 20. Kd2 { [%clk 0:00:21] } 20... Nxe4+ { [%clk 0:00:38] } 21. Ke3 { White's king is perfectly safe. The game is over, as♘f6+ cannot be stopped. } { [%clk 0:00:17] } 21... Qe1+ { [%clk 0:00:29] } 22. Rxe1 { [%clk 0:00:15] } 22... Re8 { [%clk 0:00:27] } 23. Nf6+ { [%clk 0:00:14] } 23... Nexf6 { [%clk 0:00:26] } 24. Qh8# { 1-0 White wins by checkmate. } { A nice attacking game by @Ben2020Tor! } { [%clk 0:00:13] } 1-0


