[StudyName "Game Of The Month - September 2025"]
[ChapterName "Prayer791 (2521) - Ze-Prodigy (2390)"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/RBjcNmNL/8RXgzJft"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NaSil"]

{ There are good reasons why off-beat opening lines are rarely seen. In September GOTM we get to see some of the underlying facts that so-called Levitsky Attack is seldom played, of course with imaginative attacking display. Enjoy! }
1. d4 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 1... d5 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 2. Bg5 { This move, which is known to be somewhat dubious, has some logic behind it. White might aim for "Torre Attack" or "London" type of development scheme with e3, Nf3, Bd3 and so on, sometimes transposing into QGD with c4 or White can aim for non-theoretical fight creating an imbalanced position from the very beggining.
The move 2.Bg5 was also tried by the author of these words. Quite surprisingly it worked well in practice for me, mainly due to the early bishop move is a rare guest in tournament practice. } { [%clk 0:02:59] } 2... f6 { This ambitious move preparing ...e5 with tempo shares first place with 2...c5 on Stockfish's preference list at a respectable depth by a very small margin. } { [%clk 0:02:59] } (2... c5 { Second top choice of our beloved friend, Stockfish. } 3. dxc5 { Planning to play c2-c4 or e2-e4. } 3... Qa5+?! { A very common imprecision. } (3... h6! { and every bishop move presents Black different possibilities. }) 4. Nc3! { [%cal Gd1d5] } 4... e6 5. e4 { White is close to be winning already as can be seen on Lichess Masters Database and my OTB game: https://lichess.org/broadcast/ergun-gumrukcuoglu-memorial-2022/round-2/L7tSUjv0/psTiZ4tL }) (2... h6 { is also reasonable to play ...c5 next with the same intentions explained above. }) (2... Nf6 { Now White can either transpose to the Trompowsky Attack with } 3. Bxf6 { or keep the flexibility with } (3. e3)) 3. Bh4 { [%clk 0:02:58] } (3. Bd2 { Not letting black to harass the bishop further is my preference. } 3... e5 4. dxe5 fxe5 5. e4 Nf6 6. exd5 Bc5 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be3 { It looks like White gets what he wanted (an unusual position!) from the opening in the game: } { Jimenez Jimenez, Leandro - Fernandez, Fe, 1/2-1/2, 17th American Cont Rapid, 2024, https://lichess.org/uyvQzDFZ }) 3... Nh6 { This is the usual follow-up to play Nf5 asking further questions to white's dark squared bishop. } { [%clk 0:02:59] } 4. f3 { Logical reaction, but this move makes it harder for White to develop. If White manages to play e4 then everything will be fine... } { [%clk 0:02:58] } (4. e3 Nf5 5. Bg3 h5! { Destoying white's pawn structure on the kingside is the idea. } { [%csl Gg3][%cal Gh5h4] }) 4... Nf5 { The most natural continuation, but here Black can change the move order to their benefit. } { [%clk 0:02:57] } (4... Nc6! { Fighting against white's e2-e4 by putting pressure on d4-square while further preparing ...e5. Accurate calculation required here: } 5. e4 dxe4 { [%cal Rd8d4,Rc6d4] } 6. d5 Nf5! 7. fxe4 (7. Bf2 e3 $19) 7... Nxh4 8. Qh5+ Ng6 9. dxc6 Qd4! { Black had the upper hand in this complicated position. } { Lasinskas, Povilas - Matsenko, Sergei, 1/2-1/2, Badalona op 35th, 2009, https://lichess.org/AE7SBGim } { [%cal Gd4e4,Gd4b2] }) (4... e6 { Black can also prepare to play the typical ...c5 to make use the weakening 4.f3 move. }) (4... c5 { is playable here as well. }) 5. Bf2 { White is ready to play e4, so... } { [%clk 0:02:57] } 5... e5!? { This might not the best move but as we'll see it becomes the pillar of White's success. } { [%clk 0:02:57] } (5... c5 { is Stockfish's top choice although it's not easy to foresee what is going on excatly after } 6. dxc5 d4 { The point of previous move. } 7. g4 { [%csl Gd4,Rf5][%cal Gf2d4,Gd1d4] } 7... Qa5+ (7... Ne3 8. Bxe3 dxe3 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Nc3 e5 11. O-O-O+ Bd7 { Even though Black scored 3/3 from this position, Stockfish likes white's position, for example: } 12. f4! { [%cal Gf1g2] } 12... exf4 13. Bg2 $14 { Drazic, Sinisa - Zhang, Pengxiang, 0-1, Cannes op, 2005, https://lichess.org/KPz2U6KM }) 8. Qd2 Qxd2+ 9. Nxd2 Ne3 10. Bxe3 dxe3 11. Nc4 Nc6 $13 { Stockfish's main line offers Black nice play with the bishop pair even if e3-pawn falls, White needs few moves to untangle the pieces on the kingside. }) 6. dxe5 { [%clk 0:02:57] } (6. e3 { Black would have a nice position after this timid move, for example } 6... exd4 7. exd4 Qe7+!? { An interesting move to create disharmony in white's camp and make use of e3-square in case. } { Rojas Keim, Luis Alberto - Pfrommer, Christoph, 1/2-1/2, Boeblingen op 26th, 2009, https://lichess.org/uTYiWBs2 }) 6... Nc6! { A typical pawn sacrifice to accelarate black's development. } { [%clk 0:02:56] } 7. exf6?! { [%clk 0:02:54] } (7. e4! { It's the best moment to strike in the center as White could not achive the desired break in the game. } 7... dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. fxe4 Nfd4 10. Bd3 fxe5 $14 { Completely symmetrical pawn structure has arisen. White might have slightly better position in this queenless middlegame because black's king makes it harder to coordinate. }) 7... Qxf6 { [%cal Gf6b2] [%clk 0:02:56] } 8. c3 { [%clk 0:02:48] } 8... Be6 { [%clk 0:02:53] } 9. Nd2 { White would like to achive e2-e4 under the best circumstances, but this will never happen. } { [%cal Ge2e4] [%clk 0:02:43] } (9. e4! dxe4 10. fxe4 Nh6 { [%csl Gg4,Gf2][%cal Gh6g4,Gg4e5,Gg4f2] } 11. h3 (11. Nf3 Ng4 12. Bh4 Qg6 13. Nbd2 Bc5 $17) 11... Bd6 12. Nf3 O-O-O 13. Bb5 $15 { [%cal Gb1d2,Ge1g1] }) 9... O-O-O { [%clk 0:02:52] } 10. Qc2 { White has 2 ideas, they would like to castle long and play e2-e4. } { [%cal Ge1c1,Ge2e4] [%clk 0:02:42] } 10... d4! { This move kills White's hopes to achieve the desired plan mentioned above. The best thing to do is to open up the position when you have the advantage in development. } { [%clk 0:02:49] } 11. Ne4 { [%clk 0:02:41] } (11. cxd4 Ncxd4 12. Qa4 Bb4 $19 { is one way to win. }) 11... Qe5 { [%clk 0:02:44] } 12. g4 { [%clk 0:02:35] } 12... Ne3! { Another strong move that compeletely boxing in white's forces. } { [%clk 0:02:40] } 13. Bxe3 { It's very hard to tolerate that strong knight. } { [%clk 0:02:33] } 13... dxe3 { [%clk 0:02:40] } 14. Bg2 { [%clk 0:02:18] } 14... Be7 { Black has completely winning position. White can not develop, white's king is in the middle of the board and black is fully mobilized with the bishop pair. } { [%cal Ge7h4] [%clk 0:02:38] } 15. Nh3 { White could have castled... } { [%cal Ge1g1] [%clk 0:02:11] } 15... Bh4+ { If black allowed it. } { [%clk 0:02:36] } 16. Kf1 { [%clk 0:02:11] } 16... Rhf8 { [%cal Ge6g4,Gf8f1] [%clk 0:02:35] } 17. Kg1 { [%clk 0:01:55] } 17... h5 { Black has many ways to increase their advantage. } { [%csl Gg4,Gh3][%cal Ge6h3] [%clk 0:02:10] } 18. g5 { [%clk 0:01:50] } 18... Kb8 { Black has all the time to improve their position. } { [%clk 0:02:06] } 19. Rd1 { [%clk 0:01:35] } 19... Rxd1+ { [%clk 0:02:02] } 20. Qxd1 { [%clk 0:01:34] } 20... Rd8 { [%clk 0:02:01] } 21. Qc2 { [%clk 0:01:32] } 21... Nb4!! { As White is completely tied up, there are many ways to win, but this is a flashy one! } { [%clk 0:01:46] } 22. cxb4 { [%clk 0:01:27] } (22. Qb1 { This move seems to be a better practical choice, but White is lost anyway. } 22... Bxh3 23. Bxh3 Nd5 { Black will completely shut white's rook and the king in the corner with the next move. } { [%cal Gd5f4] } 24. Qd1 { [%cal Gd1d8] } 24... Qe7 25. c4 Nf4 26. Qf1 Rd2 $19 { [%csl Gd2][%cal Ge4d2,Ge3d2] }) 22... Qxb2!! { The point of previous move! Black tries to reach white's king via back rank. } { [%clk 0:01:45] } 23. Qxb2 { [%clk 0:01:24] } 23... Rd1+ { [%clk 0:01:43] } 24. Bf1 { [%clk 0:01:22] } 24... Bxh3 { [%clk 0:01:41] } 25. Ng3 { A picturesque position, white can not prevent mate even if it's their move in this position. White's pieces are in zugzwang on the kingside. } { [%clk 0:01:20] } 25... Rxf1+ { [%clk 0:01:34] } 26. Nxf1 { [%clk 0:01:19] } 26... Bf2# { 0-1 Black wins by checkmate. } { A beautiful finish to a lovely game! } { [%clk 0:01:33] } 0-1


