{ The goal of a good analysis is to leave the reader with a deeper understanding than they had before reading it. In this article, I will strive to take the reader even further, as I personally gained great insights while conducting the analysis of 2024 March Game of The Month. }
1. c4 { Why has 1.c4 become popular in chess? One possible reason is to avoid well-known theory, while another could be the ability for White to play d2-d4 and transpose into Queen's Pawn Openings. In the upcoming game, we will not see the d-pawn moving forward at all! } { [%clk 0:03:00] } 1... c6 { Black intends to play the Slav Defense, one of the most dynamic and reliable defensive systems for black. } { [%clk 0:03:00] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 0:03:01] } 2... d5 { [%clk 0:03:01] } 3. e3! { While writing the annotations, I researched extensively but was unable to find the name of the variation. It is possible that it does not exist or that it is considered a subvariation of the Reti or English opening. White had the option to play 2.d4 or 3.d4, but instead chose to avoid this in order to pave the way for their bishop to have a strong presence on the a1-h8 diagonal.
This is a modern approach that not only protects the c4-pawn, but also prevents the opponent from pushing their d-pawn to d4. } { [%clk 0:03:02] } 3... e6 { Black plays solidly and maintains the option of playing ...f5, should they choose to play the Stonewall variation of the Dutch Defence. The most commonly played move in this position is 3...Nf6, which keeps the c8-Bishop's diagonal open. However, this bishop may not have a promising future in the game. } { [%clk 0:03:02] } (3... Nf6 { and now If White would like to prevent black from developing their light squared bishop, they should play } 4. Nc3 { to use the b3-square in case of 4...Bf5 or 4...Bg4, for instance } { [%cal Gd1b3] } 4... Bf5 (4... Bg4 { will lead you to 5th chapter. }) 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 { Stean - Birnboim 1978, first game that was played in this line you can find in the next chapters of the study. } { [%cal Gb3d5,Gb3b7] }) 4. b3 { As mentioned in the previous note, Black did not play 3...Nf6, so White does not need to refrain from making this move. } { [%clk 0:03:02] } 4... Bd6 { [%clk 0:03:00] } (4... f5 { The Stonewall Dutch Defence is generally considered to be strategically risky, but it can still be played in order to create a lively game. In this particular instance, White may have an advantage by not playing d2-d4. Play might continue; } 5. Be2 (5. Bb2 { perfectly playable as well. }) 5... Nf6 6. O-O Bd6 7. Ba3 { One argument against playing Bb2 too early is to consider the benefits of exchanging the dark-squared bishops, as it is the main defender of the e5-square. To further support this point, I recommend taking a look at a good example of playing against the Stonewall Dutch by Victor Laznicka in the next chapters of the study. This game is worth analyzing for its strategic concepts as well. } 7... e5!? { Despite the fact that the Masters Database did not include this move, our daring Lichess users still choose to play it. So we can call it Lichess Variation may be? }) 5. Bb2 { [%cal Gb2g7] [%clk 0:03:03] } 5... Nf6 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 6. g4!? { A more modern way of playing, although quite common in blitz games, is very risky. However, who doesn't enjoy taking risks once in a while? This position has also been seen in master-level play at the beggining of the new millenium! Stockfish doesn't like this move but doesn't hate it as well. } { [%csl Gg5][%cal Gg4g5,Rb2g7] [%clk 0:03:04] } 6... O-O { Cool as cucumber black castles into it as it's the best way to repel g4-g5 threat. } { [%clk 0:02:58] } (6... Nxg4 7. Rg1 { This is the obvious point of white's agressive thrust. }) 7. g5 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 7... Ne4! { 2024 March's Game of The Month witnesses rare line according to Masters' Database, but Lichess Database has close to 200 games in this position! } { [%csl Bg5][%cal Gd8g5,Be4g5] [%clk 0:02:59] } (7... Nfd7 8. h4 e5 { Countering white's offensive in the center! } { Dzagnidze, N. - Muzychuk, A., 1/2-1/2, Olympiad Women 2018, https://lichess.org/qiY6WqYt }) 8. h4 { [%clk 0:03:00] } (8. Rg1 { Stockfish's choice! Our silicon friend quiet understandably keep the option of sacrificing the g5-pawn and place the rook on the g-file cooperating with the bishop on b2. } { [%csl Gg8][%cal Gg1g8] } 8... e5 { would be a mistake now, as White can just take it. See next note. } 9. Nxe5 Nxg5 { and Black king would feel the pressure. } { [%cal Gg1g8,Gb2g7] }) 8... dxc4 { "An attack on the wing should be met by a counter in the center!" - Black probably felt the urgency to answer white attack on the kingside, but this move helps white developing their bishop and more importantly with this move black hands over the center without justification.
A proper way to "counter in the center" is } { [%clk 0:02:23] } (8... e5! { Amazing resource! It's not clear how white should react as black might continue with ...f7-f6 or ...f7-f5 } 9. Nxe5? (9. Bxe5 Bxe5 10. Nxe5 f6) 9... f6! { Stockfish shows us the way. Black is already close to winning. } { [%cal Gf8f2] } 10. gxf6 Nxf2!! { Only Stockfish can play like this! } (10... Qxf6 { A human would play like this and enjoy the counterplay. }) 11. f7+! (11. Kxf2 Qxf6+ { [%cal Gf6b2,Gf8f2] }) 11... Rxf7!! 12. Nxf7 Nxh1 13. Nxd8 Bg3+ 14. Ke2 Bg4+ 15. Kd3 Bxd1 16. Nxb7 Nf2+ 17. Kc3 Nd7 { Let suppose we calculate this line while playing 10...Nxf2 we might think white's a pawn up, but in fact white forces are not properly placed and their king is exposed. Stockfish considers this poisiton as close to a full point. }) 9. Bxc4 { [%clk 0:02:47] } 9... b6 { Planning to exchange the bishops, but this is rather slow. Black should strive for counterplay. The logical plan might be insisting on the central counterplay by ...f5 to open the f-file or strengthen the Ne4. } { [%clk 0:01:55] } 10. Qc2 { [%clk 0:02:21] } 10... Nc5 { [%clk 0:01:53] } (10... f5? { This move seems long overdue } 11. gxf6 Nxf6 12. Ng5! { White has a crushing attack. } { [%cal Gc2h7,Gb2f6,Gc4e6] }) 11. b4 { White doesnt want to block the long diagonal with 11.d4 but Stockfish likes to occupy the squares with pawns and proceeds with Nbd2, 0-0-0 or Ke2, h5-g6-h6 depending on circumstances. The text is also good but Stockfish realizes a tactical subtlety. } { [%clk 0:02:14] } 11... Ncd7 { [%clk 0:01:52] } (11... Na4! { Black strongly desires to exchange one of these powerful bishops. This move which gives some counterplay for black is the reason that 11.b4 was not a great choice according our silicon friend. } { [%csl Gb2,Gc4][%cal Gc2a4,Gb6b5] }) 12. Bd3! { White mercilessly asks black to make a pawn move in front of their king. } { [%clk 0:01:59] } 12... g6 { A hook! } { [%clk 0:01:37] } (12... f5 13. gxf6 Nxf6 14. Ng5! (14. Bxf6?? { we should not even calculate this move. } 14... Qxf6 15. Bxh7+ Kh8 { [%cal Gf6f3,Gf6a1] }) 14... h6 15. Bc4 { and the attack continues... } { [%csl Gf6,Gh7][%cal Gc2h7,Gb2f6] }) 13. h5 { Black has full army on the queenside waiting to be developed while white is having all the fun on the kingside. White would like to destroy the king's cover now. } { [%csl Gg6][%cal Rh5g6,Rd3g6] [%clk 0:01:39] } 13... Qe8 { [%cal Ge8g6] [%clk 0:00:59] } 14. Nc3! { White doesn't care about the b4-pawn. } { [%clk 0:00:30] } 14... Ba6 { [%clk 0:00:49] } (14... Bxb4 15. Ne4 { White simply place their queen on c3 and crush on the long diagonal for example: } 15... Ba6 16. Bxa6 Nxa6 17. a3 Be7 (17... Ba5 { [%csl Gc3][%cal Gc2c3,Ga5c3] } 18. Nd6 Qe7 19. hxg6 fxg6 20. Qxg6+! { Another illustrative point of white's attack. }) 18. hxg6 fxg6 (18... hxg6 19. Rh8#) 19. Qc3) 15. Be4 { White doesn't want to contribute black's development by exchanging on a6. } { [%clk 0:00:26] } 15... Bxb4 { [%clk 0:00:40] } 16. O-O-O { [%clk 0:00:24] } 16... Nc5 { Black will complete their development with Nbd7 at last! The problem is that white is fully mobilized and about to play the decisive blow. } { [%clk 0:00:15] } 17. hxg6 { [%clk 0:00:21] } 17... fxg6 { [%clk 0:00:15] } (17... hxg6 18. Nd5 { [%csl Gb2][%cal Gh1h8,Gd5f6] }) 18. Rxh7!! { The cleanest way to victory. } { [%clk 0:00:15] } 18... Kxh7 { [%clk 0:00:12] } 19. Rh1+ { [%clk 0:00:16] } 19... Kg8 { [%clk 0:00:09] } 20. Bxg6 { [%clk 0:00:16] } 20... Qe7 { [%clk 0:00:09] } 21. Nd5! { The game is over. What is more impressive about this game is that both sides played this complicated middlegame under a minute. } { [%cal Gb2h8,Gh1h8] [%clk 0:00:15] } 21... Qg7 { [%clk 0:00:07] } 22. Bxg7 { The awake reader might spot the faster mate in two, starting with Ne7+. Yet, with low time on the clock, it's very natural to take the hanging queen, which also ends in mate. } { [%clk 0:00:14] } (22. Ne7+! Qxe7 23. Rh8#) 22... Kxg7 { [%clk 0:00:09] } 23. Rh7+ { [%clk 0:00:15] } 23... Kg8 { [%clk 0:00:10] } 24. Ne7# { We can draw some conclusions about this very short but instructive game.
-It's very important to have good control over the central squares. In the game black relinquished the center with 8...dxc4 which was the beggining of their troubles.
-Stockfish's masterful creation of counterplay on the 8th move is testimony to how important it is to answer the question of how to counter a pawn offensive on one side of the board.
-Having an understanding of typical middlegame positions from a particular opening is a crucial aspect of blitz chess. White chose a highly aggressive opening in this game and utilized their knowledge of the middlegame positions that had arisen on the board.
In the next chapters of the study, I will provide illustrative games to help you understand the typical middlegame positions of this line. } { [%clk 0:00:13] } 1-0


