{ Every opening and every structure has its own features. For example closed or semi-closed positions may include problematic pieces due to arising pawn structure. April's Game Of The Month effectively demonstrates the benefits of having space advantage and importance of piece placement. }
1. Nf3 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 1... d6 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 2. d4 { [%clk 0:02:52] } 2... Bg4 { The idea of this move is to keep the central structure flexible until black decides how to react white's intentions. There are possible scenarios, black can try playing
- e6-d5 since they've already developed their light squared bishop,
- like "Old Indian" with d6-Nd7-e5 depending on their mood or white's play.
Even though i had also played this move previously i was not aware of its name. This is called Wade Defence according to Lichess Database and Wikipedia. } { [%clk 0:02:59] } 3. Nfd2!? { This is obviously contrary to the principle "do not move the same piece twice in the opening unless it's necessary". White decides to play against black's light squared bishop without letting black exchange it with the knight and it works like a charm in the game as you'll see. } { [%clk 0:02:49] } 3... Nf6 { [%csl Gf3,Ge4][%cal Gf2f3,Ge2e4] [%clk 0:02:58] } (3... d5 { Not giving up the center which white will soon occupy with their pawns. We might start counting tempi comparing it other 1.d4 d5 openings. }) 4. f3 { [%clk 0:02:47] } 4... Bh5 { [%clk 0:02:57] } (4... Bd7 { With the hindsight, this might be a better alternative if black'd like to play ...e7-e5. }) 5. e4 { [%clk 0:02:45] } 5... e5 { Black decided against e6-d5 ideas, but we shall see this will not end up nicely for their minor pieces. } { [%clk 0:02:56] } (5... e6 { To improve the quality of light squared bishop's life. } { [%cal Gd6d5] }) 6. d5! { Simple yet effective! White gets a nice space advantage. This structure arises from many openings like King's Indian Defence, Old Indian Defence or Philidor Defence. Since black has less space they'd like to exchange pieces and try to break white's strong pawn chain by ...f7-f5 or ...c7-c6. The former would be more useful but looking at black's minor piece placement, this doesn't seem achievable for the time being. } { [%clk 0:02:44] } 6... Nbd7 { [%clk 0:02:55] } 7. Qe2 { I'd love to put a bishop here but it doesn't matter a lot, since black can not open up the position white might loose some time. } { [%clk 0:02:38] } 7... c6 { [%clk 0:02:54] } 8. c4! { Strengthening the grip. } { [%clk 0:02:36] } 8... Qc7 { [%clk 0:02:53] } 9. g4 { Theoretically speaking black's dark squared bishop is a "bad bishop" but since their light squared bishop is also misplaced one can not call Bh5 a "good bishop" which is also buried by white pawns. How about black knights? They also do not seem too happy neither, but c5-square is availabe for one of them after a possible ...a7-a5. } { [%csl Gf8,Gh5] [%clk 0:02:35] } 9... Bg6 { [%clk 0:02:52] } 10. h4 { [%clk 0:02:35] } 10... h6 { [%clk 0:02:51] } (10... h5 { to let a further squeeze or not, is not an easy question to answer but may be preferable to try breaking open white's wall of pawns at some stage. } 11. g5 Nh7 { [%cal Gf7f6] }) 11. h5 { [%clk 0:02:33] } 11... Bh7 { "Capablanca bishop" is on the board as you might find in the next chapters of this study. } { [%clk 0:02:50] } 12. Nc3 { [%clk 0:02:32] } 12... Be7 { [%clk 0:02:49] } 13. Nb3 { If white can develop freely they'll have crushing advantage. } { [%clk 0:02:28] } 13... a6?! { The most critical moment of the game for black! Black might use the opportunity by playing } { [%clk 0:02:48] } (13... a5! { [%csl Gc5][%cal Ba5a4,Gd7c5] } 14. Be3 a4 15. Nd2 Nc5 { Then black has a very nice idea of regrouping their minor pieces. One line to illustrate the point of Black's intentions, } { [%csl Gg5][%cal Gf6d7,Gc7d8,Ge7g5] } 16. Qd1 Nfd7! 17. Be2 Qd8! { [%cal Ge7g5] } 18. O-O Bg5! { and black should not be worse at all, as they can organize ...g7-g6, ...f7-f5. Of course white could do better in the meantime but this is a line to show how black should seek exchanges and improving their minor pieces' positions. }) 14. Be3 { [%clk 0:02:26] } 14... cxd5 { [%clk 0:02:47] } 15. cxd5 { [%clk 0:02:25] } 15... b5 { A weakening move or a beggining of a counterattack? Since white's essentially a piece up on the queenside (because of Bh7) this is more of a weakening move. } { [%csl Rc6] [%clk 0:02:45] } 16. Rc1 { [%csl Gb5][%cal Gc1c7,Gc3b5] [%clk 0:02:21] } 16... Qb7 { [%clk 0:02:43] } 17. a3 { [%clk 0:02:08] } (17. Na5 { would obviously be better to invade the c6-square at once. } { [%csl Ga5,Gc6,Gb7][%cal Ga5c6] }) 17... Bd8 { Black stops Na5 and prepares Bb6 to exchange their bad bishop. } { [%csl Rb6,Ya5][%cal Rd8b6,Bb3a5,Gb6a5] [%clk 0:02:41] } 18. Na2 { White's feels the wall of pawns in the center guarantees to move freely on the queenside, but there is a tactical chance for black to change the character of the game. } { [%cal Ga2b4,Gb4c6] [%clk 0:02:06] } 18... Bb6 { [%clk 0:02:40] } (18... Nxe4! 19. fxe4 Bxe4 20. Bg2 Bxd5 { Black would get 3 pawns for the knight. 2 central passed pawns, white king somewhat exposed black should have counterplay here. }) 19. Nb4 { [%clk 0:02:05] } 19... Bxe3 { It was not necessary to improve white's forces but black's position is already very difficult. } { [%clk 0:02:39] } 20. Qxe3 { [%clk 0:02:04] } 20... O-O { [%clk 0:02:34] } 21. Nc6 { [%clk 0:02:03] } 21... Kh8 { [%clk 0:02:16] } 22. Nba5 { [%clk 0:02:01] } 22... Qb6 { [%clk 0:02:08] } 23. Qxb6 { [%clk 0:01:47] } 23... Nxb6 { At first sight black might be happy to exchange the queens but the problems of their position are not easily solvable. Black minor pieces lack squares and whites forces are better then their counterparts. } { [%clk 0:02:08] } 24. b3 { [%csl Gb6][%cal Gb6c4,Gb6a4] [%clk 0:01:46] } (24. Nb7 { at once would tie down black's forces even further as happened a move later in the game. }) 24... Kg8 { [%clk 0:02:03] } (24... Nxe4 { Stockfish still prefers to sacrifice the knight for two pawns to get some play. }) 25. Nb7 { [%csl Gd6][%cal Gb7d6] [%clk 0:01:44] } 25... Nc8 { [%clk 0:02:00] } 26. Kd2! { Exclamation point is not for the strength of the move but the idea to use the king to invade. } { [%csl Ga6][%cal Gd2c3,Gc3b4,Gb4a5] [%clk 0:01:36] } 26... Re8 { [%clk 0:01:59] } 27. Kc3 { [%clk 0:01:35] } 27... Nd7 { [%clk 0:01:51] } 28. Kb4 { [%clk 0:01:33] } 28... Nb8 { [%clk 0:01:33] } 29. Ncd8 { [%csl Gc8][%cal Gc1c7,Gc7c8] [%clk 0:01:20] } 29... Nd7 { [%clk 0:01:28] } 30. Ka5 { [%csl Ga6] [%clk 0:01:15] } 30... Ra7 { [%clk 0:01:23] } 31. Rc6 { Black's pieces can not even move, a nice illustration of space advantage and domination. I'll leave the rest of the game without further comments. } { [%csl Ga6][%cal Gc6a6] [%clk 0:01:10] } (31. Rxc8 Rxb7 32. Nxb7 Rxc8 33. Kxa6 { [%csl Gb5][%cal Gb7d6,Gf1b5] } 33... Rc1 34. Kxb5 { [%csl Gd6,Gb3,Ga3] }) 31... Rxd8 { [%clk 0:01:10] } 32. Nxd8 { [%clk 0:01:07] } 32... Ra8 { [%clk 0:01:04] } 33. Rxa6 { [%clk 0:01:04] } 33... Rb8 { [%clk 0:01:02] } 34. Nc6 { [%clk 0:01:02] } 34... Rb7 { [%clk 0:01:00] } 35. Ra8 { [%clk 0:01:01] } 35... Rc7 { [%clk 0:00:59] } 36. Bxb5 { [%clk 0:00:59] } 36... Nc5 { [%clk 0:00:57] } 37. Rb1 { [%clk 0:00:55] } 37... g6 { [%clk 0:00:54] } 38. Ba6 { [%clk 0:00:53] } 38... Nxa6 { [%clk 0:00:49] } 39. Kxa6 { [%clk 0:00:53] } 39... gxh5 { [%clk 0:00:47] } 40. gxh5 { [%clk 0:00:53] } 40... f5 { [%clk 0:00:43] } 41. Rxc8+ { 1-0 Black resigns. } { [%clk 0:00:51] } 1-0


