1. d4 { [%eval 0.15] [%clk 1:24:19] } 1... Nf6 { [%eval 0.16] [%clk 1:28:02] } 2. Bf4 { [%eval 0.11] [%clk 1:24:47] } 2... d5 { [%eval 0.0] [%clk 1:27:59] } 3. e3 { [%eval 0.08] [%clk 1:25:13] } 3... c5 { [%eval 0.15] [%clk 1:28:23] } 4. c3 { [%eval 0.0] [%clk 1:25:37] } 4... Nc6 { [%eval 0.0] [%clk 1:27:58] } 5. Nd2 { [%eval 0.0] [%clk 1:26:04] } 5... Bf5 { [%eval 0.0] [%clk 1:27:27] } 6. a4!? { [%eval 0.0] } { A rather curious idea that one can learn from this game. Even though i played London System from time to time, this idea never occured to me. White basically wants to meet 6...Qb6 with 7.Ra2 and a start of a possible expansion with b4 in the future depending on the position. Correspondance chess players tried this move to get new battlegrounds in this rather teoretical line. } { [%clk 1:26:32] } (6. Ngf3 Qb6 { is the main line. }) 6... a6 { [%eval 0.0] [%clk 1:24:37] } (6... Qb6 7. Ra2) 7. Ngf3 { [%eval 0.04] [%clk 1:26:51] } 7... e6 { [%eval 0.0] [%clk 1:24:47] } 8. Be2 { [%eval 0.04] [%clk 1:23:30] } 8... Rc8 { [%eval 0.12] [%clk 1:11:55] } (8... Be7 9. O-O Qb6 10. Ra2 O-O 11. dxc5 { This is one of the ideas behind this variation. } 11... Qxc5 12. Nb3 Qa7 13. a5 { 6.a4 becomes useful as it fixes black's strucutre on the queenside. } 13... h6 14. Nbd4 Bh7 15. h3 Rfc8 16. Qa4 Ne4 { Höppenstein, Michael - Burmeister, Ferdinand, 1/2-1/2, WC22/SF/5, 2019, https://lichess.org/I45glQT4 }) 9. O-O { [%eval 0.14] [%clk 1:15:02] } 9... cxd4 { [%eval 0.09] [%clk 1:02:58] } 10. exd4 { [%eval 0.12] } { We are witnessing another Carlsbad Structure from Deac's practice in this tournament. } { [%clk 1:10:54] } 10... Nd7 { [%eval 0.53] } { Probably worried about Nh4 ideas Deac makes a move to control e5-square, but this gives white an interesting possibilty. } { [%clk 1:03:24] } 11. b4!? { [%eval 0.36] } { Similar to Deac's opponent in the second round game White tries to play on the queenside. White will try to play a5 and control dark squares while black might try to play ...e5 to attack c3-pawn. } { [%clk 1:03:32] } 11... Ne7 { [%eval 0.85] [%csl Gc3][%cal Gc8c3,Ge7g6] [%clk 0:51:05] } 12. Qb3 { [%eval 0.87] [%clk 0:52:38] } 12... Ng6 { [%eval 0.93] [%clk 0:48:12] } 13. Be3?! { [%eval 0.24] } { White probably disliked the possiblity of White's kingside play with h5-h4 and put his bishop into a more passive position. } { [%clk 0:44:43] } (13. Bg3 h5 14. h3 h4 15. Bh2 Be7 16. a5 O-O 17. b5 { One possible line that shows one of the ideas of white's queenside play. }) 13... Be7 { [%eval 0.19] [%clk 0:43:32] } 14. h3 { [%eval 0.19] [%clk 0:41:21] } 14... O-O { [%eval 0.19] [%clk 0:41:40] } 15. Rac1 { [%eval -0.08] [%clk 0:36:32] } (15. a5 { It would be interesting to see how black would react against the idea mentioned above. } { [%cal Gb4b5,Gc3c4] }) (15. g4 { would be very risky but playable } 15... Be4 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Nd2 Nf6 18. c4 Bd6 $13 { [%cal Gg6f4] }) 15... Nf6 { [%eval 0.09] [%clk 0:37:50] } 16. Ne5 { [%eval 0.09] [%cal Gg2g4,Rf5e4,Bf2f3] [%clk 0:30:28] } 16... h5 { [%eval 0.25] [%clk 0:36:24] } 17. g4?? { [%eval -2.11] } { Suddenly black decides to go all in but the underlying reasons are not clear to me. } { [%clk 0:26:48] } (17. a5 Bd6) 17... hxg4 { [%eval -2.12] [%clk 0:36:42] } 18. hxg4 { [%eval -2.23] [%clk 0:27:17] } 18... Nxe5 { [%eval -2.21] [%clk 0:37:04] } 19. gxf5 { [%eval -2.2] [%clk 0:27:28] } 19... Neg4 { [%eval -2.27] [%clk 0:36:46] } 20. Bf4 { [%eval -3.06] [%clk 0:17:34] } (20. fxe6 Qd6! { White might have missed that this looses while playing 17.g4. }) 20... Bd6 { [%eval -1.88] [%clk 0:36:10] } (20... Nh5 { Engine's choice before taking on f5. }) 21. Bg5 { [%eval -1.84] [%clk 0:17:49] } 21... exf5 { [%eval -1.14] [%clk 0:35:59] } 22. Qb1? { [%eval -2.92] } { White is pawn down with no compansation and his king is weak but Stockfish would like to take the knight at once since black can not capture with the knight. } { [%clk 0:10:11] } (22. Bxg4 fxg4 23. Kg2) 22... Qd7 { [%eval -2.78] [%clk 0:26:26] } 23. f