{ In 2025 March Game Of The Month we'll witness a discussion in the King's Indian Defence. In the opening sometimes a single loss of a tempo is decisive, but sometimes being tempo down might bring benefits as well. We'll see an exciting attack by a GM. Enjoy! }
1. c4 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 1... e5 { [%clk 0:03:00] } (1... Nf6 2. Nc3 g6 3. e4 d6 4. d4 Bg7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5 { Check the annotations of the 6th move for more details. }) 2. Nc3 { [%clk 0:02:59] } 2... Nc6 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 3. Nf3 { [%clk 0:02:59] } 3... d6 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 4. d4 { [%clk 0:02:56] } 4... g6 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 5. e3 { [%clk 0:02:49] } (5. dxe5 { Preventing Black from castling with this move is possible, but even though Black king would remain in the center White's chances to benefit from it without the queens on the board is close to zero. } 5... Nxe5 6. Nxe5 dxe5 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bg5+ f6 9. O-O-O+ Bd7 $10 { There's not a single problem for Black in this position. } { [%cal Gc7c6,Gd8c7] }) (5. d5 { This is also playable. }) 5... Bg7 { [%clk 0:02:58] } 6. Be2 { [%clk 0:02:49] } 6... Nh6 { Black's intention is clear and somewhat time-consuming. They would like to expand with ...f7-f5 directly or after regrouping the knight to the f7-square. } { [%clk 0:02:55] } (6... Nf6 { We do not know whether White intended to play d4-d5 after this move as well, but this gives us an interesting starting point for discussion. If White continued in the same way as in the game } 7. d5 Ne7 8. e4 O-O { This leads to a position where White plays the famous main line of the King's Indian Defence tempo down: 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5 Ne7 (check the 1st move's annotations) in this line white castled already which looks like an improvement for White, but people consider this as an invitation to play for kingside initiative to restrict Black's counterplay starting with ...f5. I would like to share a very instructive game which was played in 1983(!): } 9. h4!? c6 10. Nd2 { [%cal Gh4h5,Ge2h5] } 10... Ne8 11. h5 f5 12. hxg6 Nxg6 13. exf5 Bxf5 { [%csl Ge4] } 14. Nde4 { As a result of the h-pawn march, White has gained control over the light squares escpecially e4-square! } 14... Nf4 15. Bf3 Rc8 16. g3 cxd5 17. cxd5 Ng6 18. Bg4! { To exchange Black's best piece! } 18... Qd7 19. Bxf5 Qxf5 20. Qe2 a6 { [%cal Gb7b5,Gb5b4,Bc8c4] } 21. a4 Ne7 22. Bg5 Rf7 23. a5 Ng6 24. Ra4! Bf8 { [%csl Ge7][%cal Gf8e7] } 25. Rb4 $16 { Sunye Neto, Jaime - Giardelli, Sergio Carlos, 1/2-1/2, Curitiba, 1983, https://lichess.org/VybtDk0C } { Game ended in a draw here according the the Masters' Database, but all of White's pieces are better placed then their counterparts. With a nice control over the e4-square, white has much better position. } { [%csl Rb7] }) 7. d5! { Now this makes even more sense considering the analysis above. White's idea of playing h2-h4 will gain even more power due to the placement of the king's knight on h6. } { [%clk 0:02:27] } 7... Ne7 { [%clk 0:02:54] } 8. e4 { As we've already discussed it seems that white lost a tempo by playing e2-e4 in two moves, but this might be beneficial as we shall see. As Dvoretsky put it: "In actual fact there are no easy tasks in chess, and an extra tempo doesn't always bring gains." (Opening Preparation, 1994) } { [%clk 0:02:26] } 8... f6 { This move with the intention of playing ...Nh6-f7 is solid. } { [%cal Gh6f7] [%clk 0:02:52] } (8... f5 { This aggresive move has an instructive drawback as can be seen in the following game: } { [%cal Gh6f7] } 9. Ng5! { Preventing Black's knight from coming into play. } 9... fxe4 { [%cal Gh6f5] } (9... Nf7 10. Ne6! { Another typical idea of diverting Black's forces and opening up the d-file while clearing the d5-square. } 10... Bxe6 11. dxe6 Nh6 12. Bg5 { [%cal Gc3d5,Gg5d8] } 12... c6 13. Qb3 $18 { Black's position looks hopeless here. } { [%csl Gd6][%cal Ge1c1,Rd1d6] }) 10. g4! { a very instructive idea to remember, white restricts all the three of black's minor pieces (Bc8, Ne7, Nh6) with one move! } 10... O-O 11. Ngxe4 Bd7 12. h4 $16 $40 { Rajkovic, Dusan - Krnic, Zdenko, 1-0, YUG-ch, 1981, https://lichess.org/zYsb1YqJ }) 9. h4! { Had white already castled this might not be good idea. Here we see the benefits of losing a tempo by white. } { [%clk 0:02:17] } 9... Nf7 { [%clk 0:02:46] } 10. h5 { [%clk 0:02:16] } 10... Bh6 { A logical move to exchange Black's bad bishop, but this idea costs Black even more time. } { [%clk 0:02:46] } (10... g5? { After this move to keep things closed, White might prepare g4 and clamp down f5-square. } 11. Rg1 { and weakening the f4-square after g2-g4 will not make any impact as black's knights can never reach the f4-squre. } { [%cal Gg2g4] }) (10... f5 { Black might have started the long-awaited counterplay on the kingside typical of the King's Indian Defence. }) 11. Bxh6 { [%clk 0:02:13] } 11... Nxh6 { [%clk 0:02:46] } 12. hxg6 { [%clk 0:02:12] } 12... hxg6 { [%clk 0:02:46] } 13. Qd2 { White makes every move with tempo while Black is having hard time coordinating their forces. } { [%csl Gh6] [%clk 0:02:12] } 13... Neg8 { [%clk 0:02:39] } (13... Nf7? 14. Rxh8+ Nxh8 15. Qh6 Nf7 (15... Kf7 16. Qh7+ $18 { [%cal Gh7h8,Gh7f7] }) 16. Qg7 $18 { [%csl Gg6,Gf6][%cal Gg7f6,Ge1c1] }) (13... g5 { invites sacrifical play due to bad placement of Black's forces. } 14. Nxg5! fxg5 15. Qxg5 Neg8 (15... Nf7 16. Rxh8+ Nxh8 17. Qg7 $18 { [%cal Ge2h5] }) 16. Bh5+ Kd7 17. Qg7+ { [%cal Gg7h8,Gg7d7] } 17... Ne7 18. Bg4+ $18) 14. O-O-O { White completed their development and Black has still got few problems with their pieces. Even though position is closed, this does not guarentee Black an easy game. } { [%clk 0:02:02] } 14... Kf7 { Black might try Kg7-Nf7 to relieve the pressure on the h-file. } { [%cal Gf7g7] [%clk 0:02:38] } 15. g4!? { White doesn't want to loose time and decided to act before black plays Kg7. } { [%clk 0:01:46] } (15. Nh4 { Stockfish would like to attack in a different fashion. } 15... Kg7 16. g3! { [%csl Gf4][%cal Gf2f4] } (16. f4 { The direct move might complicate things a bit. } 16... exf4 17. Qxf4 g5 18. Qg3 Nf7 { [%csl Re5][%cal Rf7e5] }) 16... Bd7 17. f4 $40 { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gf4f5] }) 15... Bxg4? { This move is the start of Black's problems as g-file is now open for white's attack. } { [%clk 0:02:30] } (15... Kg7! { Anyway! Black should've continued their plan. } { [%cal Gh6f7] } 16. g5 Nf7 17. Rxh8 Kxh8 $14 { still looked fairly solid for Black. }) 16. Nxe5+ { As expected! } { [%clk 0:01:45] } 16... fxe5 { [%clk 0:02:29] } 17. Bxg4 { [%clk 0:01:45] } 17... Qf6 { [%clk 0:02:26] } 18. Be6+ { [%clk 0:01:43] } 18... Kg7 { It looks as if Black is kind of consolidated. } { [%clk 0:02:25] } 19. Nb5! { A strong move underlining white can create problems on the queen's wing as well thanks to their more active pieces and space advantage! } { [%clk 0:01:38] } 19... Qe7 { [%clk 0:02:18] } 20. Rdg1 { [%clk 0:01:36] } (20. f4! { Stockfish again shows that this move is the fastest way to attack as Black's knights do not have control over the e5-square. } { [%csl Gf5,Gg7][%cal Gf4f5] } 20... exf4 21. Qxf4 { Now d4-square is available for white's knight and e4-e5 is on the agenda. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gb5d4,Gd4e6,Gd4f5] }) 20... a6 { [%clk 0:02:17] } (20... Rf8 { Leaving the a7-pawn might be better, but White would still have a crushing advantage even without f2-f4 idea. }) 21. f4!! { It's worth sacrificing the knight before Black plays Rf8! Black can not allow f4-f5. } { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gf4f5] [%clk 0:01:04] } (21. Nc3? Rf8! { Black has a solid defensive position for the moment, and they can regroup with Qf6, Ne7, Nf7. } { [%cal Re7f6,Rg8e7,Gh6f7] }) (21. Nxc7! { Even this move is possible as pointed out by Stockfish. } 21... Qxc7 22. Rxg6+!! Kxg6 (22... Kf8 23. b3 { calmly protecting c4-pawn to continue the assault over the Black's king, but White's attack was crushing anyway. A sample line: } { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gd2g5] } 23... Qe7 24. Rhxh6 Nxh6 25. Qxh6+! $18 { We'll see a similar motif to this one later as well. }) 23. Rg1+ Kh7 24. Qg5 $18 { Black can take on c4 with check but white will slide the king over to a1 and give mate. }) 21... exf4 { Now d4-squre is available to white pieces, and e4-e5 might come into fore. } { [%csl Gd4] [%clk 0:02:09] } (21... axb5 22. f5 { White would continue their attack similar to the previous note. } { [%cal Gg1g6] } 22... Rxa2 23. Rxg6+ Kf8 24. Rhxh6 Nxh6 25. Qxh6+!! { We've seen this motif already. }) 22. Qg2 { [%clk 0:00:42] } (22. Rxg6+! Kxg6 23. Rg1+ Kh7 24. Qg2 { [%cal Rg2g6] } 24... Qf6 { [%cal Rg2g6] } 25. e5! $18 { [%cal Gg2e4,Ge4h7] }) 22... g5 { [%clk 0:01:54] } (22... Qf6 23. Nxc7 Rf8 24. Bd7 $18 { White's knight would join the attack as well. } { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gc7e6] }) 23. Nxc7 { This is possible as Black's queen is overloaded and tied to defence of their king. } { [%csl Gg5] [%clk 0:00:40] } 23... Rf8 { [%clk 0:01:13] } (23... Qxc7 24. Qxg5+ Kf8 25. Qxf4+ Ke8 26. Rf1 { [%cal Gf4f8] } 26... Qe7 27. e5 $18 $40 { Attack would continue smoothly as Black's pieces can not even move while position is opening up further for White's heavy pieces. }) 24. e5! { White aims at Black's best defender, the queen defending the crucial g5-pawn! } { [%clk 0:00:38] } 24... f3 { [%clk 0:00:56] } (24... dxe5 25. d6 { [%csl Ge7] } 25... Qf6 (25... Qd8 26. Bd7 $18 { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gc7e6] }) 26. Nd5 Qd8 27. Qxg5+ Qxg5 28. Rxg5+ Kh7 29. d7 { A picturesque position! Black is mated in a few moves no matter what. } 29... f3 30. d8=Q Rxd8 31. Bf5#) 25. Qxg5+ { As we saw in the previous notes, White's attack is very strong even after the exchange of queens. } { [%clk 0:00:37] } 25... Qxg5+ { [%clk 0:00:54] } 26. Rxg5+ { [%clk 0:00:37] } 26... Kh7 { [%clk 0:00:54] } 27. Ne8! { 1-0 Black resigns. } { A picturesque position! Black resigned as after } { [%csl Gg7][%cal Gg5g7] [%clk 0:00:36] } 27... Rxe8 28. Bf5# { A very nice attacking game by @delta_horsey. } 1-0


