[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NaSil"]

{ Here we are again with a very nice attacking game. Beyond the joy of watching a strong attack against the castled king, this game offers valuable lessons from the December Game of the Month, including:
-- Opposite Color Bishops Favor The Attacker
-- What to avoid playing white side of the CATALAN Opening
-- How to handle the CARLSBAD Structure
-- Identifying the right exchanges and the Tarrasch rule

Enjoy! }
1. d4 { [%clk 0:10:00] } 1... Nf6 { [%clk 0:10:00] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 0:09:59] } 2... e6 { [%clk 0:09:59] } 3. g3 { This move order is designed to avoid the move 4...Bb4+ in the main line of the closed Catalan starting with } { [%clk 0:09:58] } (3. c4 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ { If you restrict the dates of your Lichess Masters' Database for the years 2000 and later, you'll see this move is the main line. }) 3... d5 { Black has additional options to exploit white's move order. } { [%clk 0:09:44] } (3... b5 { gaining space and making it harder for white to play c4 is the main line. } { [%csl Rc4][%cal Rc2c4,Gb5c4] }) (3... c5 { since white can not reply with d4-d5 as in the Benoni, this is also popular response. }) 4. Bg2 { [%clk 0:09:57] } 4... c6 { An indication that black will play Closed Catalan. } { [%clk 0:09:40] } (4... b5 { is still possible. }) (4... c5 5. c4 { is another critical line in the Catalan. }) 5. O-O { [%clk 0:09:55] } 5... Bd6 { This move signals that Black might try to arrange e6-e5 push after Nbd7. } { [%clk 0:09:39] } 6. c4 { [%clk 0:09:54] } 6... Nbd7 { [%clk 0:09:38] } (6... dxc4 { It's not easy to identify whether grabbing the c4-pawn and hold onto it is a good strategy or not, but here capturing the pawn might not be a great choice, one sample line: } 7. Nfd2 b5 8. a4 { [%cal Gg2a8,Ga1a8] } 8... Nd5 9. axb5 cxb5 10. e4 Nc7 11. e5 { There are also other ways for white to play against 6...dxc4 as well. } { [%csl Yd6][%cal Gg2a8,Re5d6] }) 7. cxd5 { White might be worried about their c4-pawn after black's last move, but Carlsbad Structure with the bishop on g2 is not considered ideal for white. Not only does white achieve little with this exchange but also pushing e2-e4 as in the main lines of Catalan will end up with an Isolated Pawn on d4 after this move. } { [%csl Rg2] [%clk 0:09:49] } (7. Qc2 { usual Catalan move. }) (7. Nbd2 { are better ways to protect the c4-pawn. }) (7. Nc3 { Arranging e4-push with Nd2 and sacrificing the c4-pawn is the most popular move in this position. } { [%cal Gf3d2,Ge2e4] }) 7... exd5 { [%csl Gc6,Gd5,Gd4,Ge2] [%clk 0:09:37] } (7... cxd5 { It makes less sense to capture "towards the center" here, since it won't get better for the bishop on c8 and knight is misplaced on d7 which should be better placed on c6 in this structure. } { [%csl Rc8,Gd7] }) 8. Nc3 { [%clk 0:09:41] } 8... O-O { A good moment to decide what to do next for white. } { [%clk 0:09:35] } 9. Bg5 { It should be considered as a risky strategy to develop without clear plan. Here it's not clear which plan white's going for. } { [%clk 0:09:21] } 9... Qc7 { Black wants to control the f4-square (to stop Bf4 after a possible h6) and get out of the pin but, this might not look like a flexible move as there might appear a rook on c1 and the queen will have to move again to a better spot. } { [%cal Gc1c7] [%clk 0:09:16] } 10. Bxf6 { The dark-squared bishop can be exchanged for a knight in the Catalan and Queen's Indian Defence for various reasons as it becomes more like a useless piece, but after the move 7.cxd5 it's harder to justify this exchange. It's better to keep the bishop or at least opt for a better exchange: } { [%clk 0:09:10] } (10. e3! { an idea to remember! } 10... h6 11. Bf4! { A typical idea to create a monster on e5! } 11... Bxf4 12. exf4 $36 { [%csl Re5][%cal Rf3e5] } (12. gxf4 { opening up the g-file + Ne5 is also good. } { [%cal Gf3e5,Gg1g8,Gg1h1,Gf1g1] })) 10... Nxf6 { [%clk 0:09:15] } 11. Rc1 { as expected black has to spend a tempo with their queen now. } { [%csl Gc7][%cal Rc3b5,Gc1c7] [%clk 0:09:08] } 11... Qe7 { [%clk 0:09:01] } 12. h3 { White wants to control g4 square, but even so this move might be criticized as having pawns on dark squares should be a better strategy for white as they have no dark squared bishop.
Let's try to understand white's possible plans at this point.
White might go for a minority attack with b4-b5 or arrange e4. The former plan might not be as effective as in the normal Carlsbad since black can throw a5 at any time to stop b4 or after white achieves b2-b4 push. The latter idea of arranging e4 push remains as the only active plan available for white, but it's not without the risks as well, as black has the bishop pair and white will have an isolated pawn after e4.
The last possible case is to have a knight on e5 and support it with f4 as can be seen in many Carlsbad Structure games which is a dynamic way to achieve e4 as well.
Notice all available plans should justify the placement of the bishop on g2. Otherwise white will risk their remaining bishop getting useless against the black's central pawn chain. So called "Tarrasch's Rule" reminds us if a piece is badly placed, the position is bad which will be the case in this game of the month. } { [%clk 0:08:54] } (12. a3 Re8 13. b4? a5! $17 { [%cal Ge7a3] }) (12. Qc2 Re8 13. Rfe1 Bg4 14. Nd2 $132 { to go for an isolated pawn for active piece play with e2-e4 push might be the only active solution to white's problems. } { [%cal Ge2e4] }) 12... Bf5 { Black's play is easier: they will plonk a knight on e4 and strike from the kingside. } { [%clk 0:08:58] } 13. Re1 { [%clk 0:08:31] } 13... Qd7 { It might be advisable for black to avoid possible counterplay by white starting with Ne5 so i'd consider } { [%clk 0:08:49] } (13... Rfe8 { controling e5 square as a prepatory way to play Qd7 } { [%cal Ge7d7] }) 14. g4 { White king is seriously weakened after this move, and white has to play very carefully as it all depends on white's dynamic counterplay in the center from now on. } { [%clk 0:06:46] } (14. Ne5!? { This might be a possible moment to confuse the matters for black. } { [%cal Ge2e4] } 14... Qe7 (14... Bxe5? 15. dxe5 $16 { and suddenly white is much better! } { [%cal Ge2e4] }) (14... Qc7 15. Nb5 $10 { [%csl Gd6,Gc7] }) 15. e4 dxe4 16. Nxe4 Nxe4 (16... Bxe5 17. Nc5!) 17. Bxe4 Bxe4 18. Rxe4 { I'd like to have my pawn on h2 but still white has reasonable play on the e-file. Notice that } 18... f6?? { actually loses to } 19. Qb3+ Kh8 (19... Rf7 20. Nxf7) 20. Ng6+ $18 hxg6 21. Rh4#) 14... Be4 { [%clk 0:08:26] } (14... Be6 15. Ne5 Qe7 16. f4 { as in the notes of 12th move white would have more active play. }) 15. Nxe4 { [%clk 0:06:15] } (15. Ne5! { Another moment to muddy the waters and may be white's last chance! White will try to use tactics to open up the center to their favour. } 15... Qe7 (15... Bxe5 16. Nxe4 dxe4? 17. dxe5 $14 { [%csl Ge4,Gd7,Gd1] }) 16. f3 Bg6 17. f4 { would provide white some play in the center. } { [%cal Ge2e4] }) 15... Nxe4 { Black has nice attacking position and f5 is in the cards. } { [%clk 0:08:23] } 16. Nd2 { This slow move is not ideal as white has to play dynamically to compensate their king's weakness, but it's already difficult position for white as black has more active pieces and a clear plan to attack white's king. } { [%cal Ra8e8,Gf7f5] [%clk 0:06:03] } (16. Ne5 Qe7 17. f3 $15 { [%cal Ge2e4] }) 16... f5! { White regrets whole h3-g4 stuff now. } { [%clk 0:08:22] } 17. Nxe4 { Unfortunately even though this looks bad, there are not so many good moves already. } { [%clk 0:05:33] } (17. f3 { would keep the f-file closed, but of course after } 17... Nxd2 18. Qxd2 Rae8 { black's attack is still very strong. } { [%cal Gf5f4,Re8e3] } 19. e3 f4) 17... fxe4 { [%clk 0:08:18] } 18. f3 { White probably rely on this move to keep everything closed, but there's no way back since white can not control even a single dark square around the king.
We'll see "the bishops of the opposite colors favor the attacker" case as practically black is attacking with extra bishop as black has no counterpart to their dark squared bishop. } { [%clk 0:05:07] } 18... e3! { A strong move cutting the board into two to break the communication of white forces with their king! } { [%clk 0:07:05] } 19. Qb3 { [%cal Gb3e3] [%clk 0:04:26] } 19... Rae8 { Every black's piece is better than it's counterpart and white king is in grave danger. } { [%csl Ge8,Gd7,Gd6,Gf8,Rg1] [%clk 0:07:00] } 20. Rc3 { [%cal Gc3e3] [%clk 0:04:14] } 20... Qe7 { slowly getting closer to white's king. } { [%cal Ge7e3] [%clk 0:06:43] } 21. Rd1 { [%clk 0:03:50] } 21... Bf4! { [%csl Re3][%cal Ge7h4,Gh4g3] [%clk 0:06:16] } 22. Qa3 { [%clk 0:03:41] } 22... Qh4 { not minding a7-pawn, black queen goes for white's king! } { [%clk 0:05:21] } (22... Qxa3?? { Only hope for white is to play a worse endgame, but this will never happen! }) 23. Qxa7 { [%clk 0:03:19] } 23... Qf2+ { [%clk 0:05:19] } 24. Kh1 { [%clk 0:03:13] } 24... Qg3 { [%clk 0:05:17] } 25. Kg1 { [%clk 0:03:08] } 25... Qh2+ { [%clk 0:05:16] } 26. Kf1 { [%clk 0:03:07] } 26... Bg3! { Black achieves the desired attacking formation and threatens to play Bf2 and Qg1! } { [%cal Rg3f2,Gh2g1] [%clk 0:05:14] } 27. Qxb7 { [%clk 0:02:30] } 27... Rxf3+! { There's an artistic yet effective solution as well! } { [%clk 0:05:10] } (27... Bf2 { would do the job as well. }) 28. exf3 { [%clk 0:02:23] } 28... e2# { 0-1 Black wins by checkmate. } { A very instructive attacking game by anandloks! } { [%clk 0:05:09] } 0-1


