{ This is a very complicated rook endgame even though it doesn't look like it. White has a clear idea of pushing the e-pawn and advancing his king and use the d-pawn as a shelter to escape from the checks as the game continuation shows. The defensive technique is instructive! }
77... Kc8? (77... Ra1 { Black should wait white's king cross the the 4th rank. } 78. Kf4 (78. e5 Ra4? { This is the wrong timing! } (78... Rb1 79. Ke4 Rb4! { and black defends } { [%cal Gc6c5] } 80. Kd3 Rb1 { and the rook is very useful on the first rank to stop white's progress } { [%cal Rb1h1,Rb1b8] }) 79. e6 Rb4 80. Rd7+ (80. Kd3 Ra4 81. Rd7+ Kc8 82. Ke4 c5 83. Kf5 cxd4 (83... Rxd4 84. Rxd4 cxd4 85. Kf6 $18) 84. Rd5 $18 { [%cal Ge6e7,Gf5f6] }) 80... Kc8 (80... Ke8 81. Rc7) 81. Rd6 Kc7 82. Rd7+ Kc8 83. Ke4 c5 84. Kf5) 78... Ra4 79. Ke5 Rb4 { and black rook can wait on the fourth rank and d4-d5 push results in Philidor position. } 80. Ra7 Rc4! 81. d5 cxd5 82. exd5 Rh4 { and with a theoretical drawn position. } { [%csl Gh6][%cal Gh4h6] }) 78. e5! { now black is never in time! } 78... Kd8 79. Ke4 Rd2 80. e6 Re2+ 81. Kf5 { and white king invades. } 81... Re1 82. Kf6 { [%cal Gg7g8] } 82... Rf1+ 83. Ke5 Rd1 84. Ra7 Rd2 85. e7+ Ke8 86. Ke6 Re2+ 87. Kd6 Kf7 88. Kxc6 Ke8 89. d5 Rc2+ 90. Kd6 Rc8 91. Ke6 Rc6+ 92. d6 1-0


