{ A very complicated rook endgame which we will see in the chess books for sure. }
57. c4!! (57. Rb8? { The game continuation } 57... Kxc3 58. Kb1 b4 59. axb4 c4 60. Rh8 Rxh8 { 0-1 Black wins. }) 57... Rc2+ (57... bxc4 58. Rb8+! Kc3 (58... Kxa3 59. Rb5) 59. Kb1 Rh1+ 60. Ka2 Kc2 61. Rb2+! { This is tablebase draw and it's still very difficult, a sample line: } 61... Kd3 62. Rg2 Rd1 { [%cal Gd1d2] } 63. Rg3+ Kc2 64. a4 c3 65. a5 c4 66. a6 Rd6 67. Rg2+ { and white will give checks after diverting the black rook. } 67... Kd3 68. a7 Ra6+ 69. Kb1 Rxa7 70. Rg3+ Kd2 71. Rg2+ Ke3 72. Rg3+ Kd4 73. Rg4+ $10) 58. Kb1 Rxc4 59. Rb8! { with a philidor position if one more pawns will be exchanged and if black tries a transition to a pawn endgame: } 59... Kxa3 60. Rxb5 Rb4+ 61. Ka1!! $10 { Only due to this resource white would hold. } 0-1


