[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Smith-Morra Gambit Accepted"]
[StudyName "Game Of The Month - October"]
[ChapterName "AlezierChessYT (2360) - GM novik70 (2507)"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/yP5cyecR/OPtJTsIu"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NaSil"]

{ What is the best way to meet the Sicilian Defense? It's a common misconception that there's one "best" way to counter the Sicilian Defense. Today we know this question is wrong! The right question might be: which variation is the most practical and dangerous choice against one of the best defences in chess theory at faster time controls! GOTM comes up one of the most attacking answers to this question, namely Smith-Morra Gambit. }
1. e4 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 1... c5 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 2. d4 { [%clk 0:02:59] } (2. c3 { The Alapin Variation can be met in many ways. The most common responses are } 2... Nf6 (2... d5)) 2... cxd4 { [%clk 0:02:59] } 3. c3 { The wild cousin of the Alapin Variation! If Black would like to avoid the invitation to the Smith-Morra Gambit, they can safely play 3...Nf6, transposing into the Alapin Variation. The problem in this case is if Black prefers to meet 2.c3 with 2...d5, they would enter an "unknown" territory. } { [%clk 0:02:58] } (3. Qxd4 { One of the more modern ways of playing against Sicilian Defense. It's comparable to fashionable line these days 1.c4 e5 2.g3 d5!? 3.cxd5 Qxd5 }) 3... dxc3 { The proof of pudding is in the eating! The "best" way to test the gambit is to take the sacrificed pawn, thus letting white show the idea of the opening. The sad part about Smith-Morra Gambit is black has many decent ways to avoid the gambit. } { [%clk 0:02:57] } (3... Nf6! { Transposing into the Alapin Variation! }) (3... d5) (3... e5!?) 4. Nxc3 { [%clk 0:02:58] } 4... e6 { If black were an inexperienced player with Smith-Morra Gambit, it would be very difficult to find the most harmonious way of developing of their pieces especially at blitz time control. In this game Grandmaster novik70 playing with the black pieces employes one of the most common lines against white's aggressive opening. } { [%clk 0:02:56] } 5. Nf3 { For White, the next few moves are fairly straightforward. Having easier time to develop thanks to the pawn sacrifice in the opening, White plans to develop with moves like Nc3, Bc4, Qe2, Rfd1, and Rac1. On an ideal day, they might even consider sacrificing additional material to open up lines against the Black king. } { [%clk 0:02:58] } 5... Nc6 { [%clk 0:02:55] } 6. Bc4 { An automatic developing move in the Morra! } { [%clk 0:02:57] } (6. Be2 { This rare move is also possible. }) 6... Nge7 { A common way to develop the knight in this line. Black's knight is heading to g6-square instead of f6 in order to avoid e4-e5 by white. The Nge7-Ng6 manuevre costs some time, but black believes solidity of their position and practice suggests if black continues carefully they should not be in danger of an immediate assault.
The main line of play is 6...a6 planning to play ...b5 and ...Bb7 and avoid any Nb5 ideas and develop the kingside pieces similar to the game continuation. } { [%clk 0:02:53] } (6... a6 { is by far the main move here. } { [%csl Gb5][%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] }) 7. O-O { Surprisingly, this position without the move ...a6 is a rare one considering the popularity of the opening. } { [%clk 0:02:56] } (7. Bg5 { Master practice more often witnesses this disruptive developing move. }) 7... Ng6 { [%clk 0:02:52] } 8. Re1 { White contradicts with my above-mentioned setup (Qe2-Rd1) but it's also very strong as we shall see. Actually this logical move eyeing at the black's king is a novelty, even though Lichess Database has almost 8500(!) games with 8.Re1 } { [%cal Ge1e8] [%clk 0:02:54] } 8... Qc7 { This move is also part of black's plans controlling the important squares like d6-e5-f4 with a certain drawback of placing the queen on a rather exposed square against various knight jumps (Nb5, Nd5) and on the open c-file opposing a potential white's rook (Rac1). Black is hoping to tuck the queen away with Qb8 against such attacks. } { [%clk 0:02:51] } (8... Be7 { black would be ready to castle with this move. }) 9. Bb3 { White moves their bishop to safety, avoiding the queen's gaze. } { [%clk 0:02:50] } (9. Nb5 Qb8 10. e5! { This pawn sacrifice is a logical continuation of the previous move; Black should decline the offer this time. } { [%cal Gb5d6] } 10... Ngxe5? (10... a6 11. Nd6+ Bxd6 12. exd6 b5 13. Bb3 Bb7 14. h4 { d6-pawn cuts the board into two and white can attack freely on the kingside, but black is still very solid.
See Milman - Ehlvest at the 3rd chapter of this study for similar structure. }) 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Bxe6!! { Clearing the c-file and weakening the black's king cover. } 12... fxe6 13. Bf4 d6 14. Rc1 $18 { White might continue with Rc7 or Nc7 depending on black's reply. } { [%cal Gc1c7,Gb5c7] }) (9. h4! { Taking advantage of the Ng6 is the best according Stockfish to continue in the AlphaZero style with h5-h6. } { [%cal Gh4h5,Gh5h6] }) 9... Be7 { Black is ready to castle finally. } { [%cal Ge8g8] [%clk 0:02:49] } 10. Nd5!? { Now or never! One of the typical ideas in the Smith-Morra Gambit is to open up lines against black king before black castles. Alternative way to increase the pressure } { [%clk 0:02:46] } (10. h4 { Stockfish considers another pawn sacrifice before black consolidates. } { [%csl Gg6][%cal Gh4h5,Gh5h6] } 10... Nxh4 11. Nxh4 Bxh4 12. e5! { This pawn can not be taken due to Bf4-Nb5 ideas. 2 pawns down but white practically has very dangerous initiative. } { [%cal Gd1g4,Gc3e4,Gg4h5] }) 10... exd5 { [%clk 0:02:45] } 11. exd5 { [%clk 0:02:46] } 11... Nce5?! { Black decides to hang onto the material which makes the situation practically more dangerous. } { [%clk 0:02:44] } (11... O-O! { It's best to give up the material to consolidate! } 12. dxc6 dxc6 { and black is a pawn up and fully mobilized. } { [%csl Gc8][%cal Gc8g4] }) 12. Nxe5 { [%clk 0:02:43] } 12... Nxe5 { [%clk 0:02:40] } 13. f4! { White will eventually gain the sacrificed piece, it's up to black how to give it back. } { [%clk 0:02:24] } (13. Bf4? d6 $19) 13... Ng6? { [%clk 0:02:35] } (13... d6! { Black has to safely blockade white's dangerous d-pawn before it's too late! } 14. fxe5 dxe5 15. Bf4! Qb6+ 16. Kh1 O-O 17. Bxe5 { [%cal Gd5d6] } 17... Bd6! { White enjoys better development and promising attacking potential, but the position remains balanced. This is due to White's passed pawn being effectively blockaded and Black's king having a solid defensive setup. }) 14. d6! { Suddenly black's situation can not be saved anymore and white will finish the game in style! } { [%clk 0:02:20] } 14... Qb6+ { Black's position is already beyond repair but Stockfish wants to control the e7-square with the queen. } { [%clk 0:02:33] } (14... Qc5+ 15. Kh1 O-O 16. dxe7 Nxe7 17. Be3! $18 { White is winning but black could play on. }) 15. Kh1 { [%clk 0:02:15] } (15. Be3?? Qxd6 $19 { is a small tactical trick to avoid. }) 15... O-O { Black has finally castled, but is that really the end of their troubles? } { [%clk 0:02:16] } 16. dxe7 { [%clk 0:02:11] } 16... Re8 { [%clk 0:02:07] } 17. Qd5! { It doesn't appear to be the case! } { [%cal Gd5f7] [%clk 0:01:41] } 17... Qf6 { [%clk 0:02:05] } 18. f5! { [%clk 0:01:38] } 18... Rxe7 { Last chance! } { [%csl Ge1][%cal Ge7e1] [%clk 0:01:35] } (18... Nh4 19. Bg5! { would be a quite nice deflection. }) (18... Nh8 { Black's knight is in the worst possible position, leaving White with a winning position regardless of their next move. }) 19. Bg5!! { The finishing touch underlining black's back-rank problems and underdeveloped pieces! With this killer blow accompanied with the next one white wins decisive material. } { [%clk 0:01:26] } 19... Qxg5 { [%clk 0:01:29] } (19... Rxe1+ 20. Rxe1 { would not save the game as well. } { [%cal Ge1e8] }) 20. fxg6! { The point of the previous move! } { [%clk 0:01:13] } 20... hxg6 { Black has no ways to survive. } { [%clk 0:01:25] } (20... Qxd5 21. Rxe7 { would be a nice double attack. } { [%csl Ge8][%cal Ge7e8,Gb3d5] }) (20... Rxe1+ 21. Rxe1 { another double attack. } { [%cal Ge1e8,Gd5f7,Gd5g5] }) (20... Qf6 { white would win in many ways, two of them are } 21. Qxf7+! (21. Rxe7 Qxe7 22. Qxf7+ Qxf7 23. Bxf7+! (23. gxf7+? Kf8 24. Re1 d5) 23... Kh8 (23... Kf8 24. Re1) 24. Re1 hxg6 25. Bxg6 { a picturesque finish reminding black's development problems. }) 21... Qxf7 (21... Rxf7 22. Re8#) 22. gxf7+ Kf8 23. Rxe7 Kxe7 24. Re1+ $18) 21. Qxg5 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { [%clk 0:01:12] } 1-0


