{ Analyzing model games is a crucial step in learning any chess opening. A short but instructive attacking game featuring Grand-Prix Attack against Sicilian Defense will be covered in the July edition of Game of the Month. }
1. e4 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 1... c5 { Sicilian Defense, that is! As we all know, it's one of of the most popular chess openings in chess history. White has many ways to deal with it, but the best method has yet to be found. } { [%clk 0:03:00] } 2. Nc3 { [%clk 0:02:57] } (2. Nf3 { If white will play the Open Sicilian then they have to be prepared against all kinds of Najdorfs, Sveshnikovs, Dragons etc. Of course there are still ways to avoid main lines like Rossolimo or Moscow variation. }) 2... d6 { Black prepares ...Nf6 without getting hit by e5 and also expects to transpose into Najdorf or Dragon after 3.Nf3, but... } { [%csl Rf6,Ye5][%cal Rg8f6,Be4e5,Yd6e5] [%clk 0:02:59] } 3. f4 { White chose the so called Grand-Prix Attack, a rather easy-to-learn attacking system for players who wish to avoid the main line theory in the Sicilian Defense. } { [%clk 0:02:53] } (3. d4 { This is another trendy way to avoid main line Sicilians nowadays. } 3... cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qd2! { We might call this the Carlsen Variation, as the former world champion introduced this line to the highest levels by beating Polish Grandmaster Radoslaw Wojtaszek in 2018. } { [%cal Gb2b3,Gc1b2] }) (3. g3 { This is Closed System, another popular way and a cousin variation of Grand-Prix Attack avoiding mainline theory. } { [%cal Gf1g2,Gf2f4,Gd2d3,Gc1e3,Gg1f3] }) 3... g6 { The most logical way of developing since now it's possible to further control dark squares with the move Bg7. } { [%cal Gf8g7] [%clk 0:02:58] } 4. Bc4 { People generally start with Nf3 as White might prefer developing the king's bishop on b5. } { [%clk 0:02:52] } (4. Nf3 Bg7 { [%csl Rb5,Bc4][%cal Rf1b5,Bf1c4] } 5. Bb5+ Bd7 6. Bc4!? { Apart from 6.a4 or 6.Bxd7, this is a curious way of disrupting black's forces. Bd7 is blocking the d-file for the queen making it harder for black to play ...d6-d5, and for example if we continue similar to the game continuation } 6... Nc6 7. O-O Nf6 { with the 5...Bd7 included White can play } 8. e5 $13 { with a complicated positon. Please compare this with notes to the move 6...e6 in the game. }) 4... Bg7 { [%clk 0:02:57] } 5. Nf3 { [%clk 0:02:50] } 5... Nc6 { [%clk 0:02:53] } 6. O-O { White's idea in the Grand-Prix Attack is to develop harmoniously and attack on the kingside by preparing, f5-Qe1-Qh4-Bh6-Ng5. } { [%csl Bf1][%cal Rf4f5,Rd2d3,Gd1e1,Be1h4,Bc1h6,Bf3g5] [%clk 0:02:49] } 6... e6 { Trying to block Bc4 and preparing Nge7. } { [%clk 0:02:53] } (6... Nf6 { To further explain the notes at the 4th move now without the bishop on d7, White can not play } 7. e5? dxe5 8. fxe5 Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Qd4+ $17 { [%cal Gd4g1,Gd4e5] }) 7. d3 { [%clk 0:02:49] } 7... Nge7 { [%clk 0:02:51] } 8. Qe1 { As mentioned at the 6th move White will carry out their attack by posting the queen aggressively and preparing Bh6 by exchanging the black's king's best defender Bg7. } { [%csl Gg7][%cal Re1h4,Gc1h6] [%clk 0:02:49] } 8... O-O { Both sides developed logically now White starts action on the kingside. } { [%clk 0:02:49] } 9. f5!? { This very typical pawn sacrifice is the most popular move according to both Masters and Lichess Database, i wonder why Stockfish doesn't like it as much. The idea is clear; opening up the f-file for the rook, c1-h6 diagonal for the queen's bishop and activating the bishop on c4. } { [%csl Rf1,Gc1][%cal Rc1h6,Bf1f8,Gc4g8] [%clk 0:02:48] } 9... gxf5! { Brave and strong! Weakening the king but believing in their defensive resources as Ng6 is possible now just in case. } { [%clk 0:02:47] } (9... d5 { This is the principal reaction as “an attack on the wing should be met by a counter in the center”. }) (9... exf5? { This is a big positional concession. Black should avoid giving up the fight against Bc4 and d5-square at once. } 10. Qh4 { As white can get an ideal attacking scheme typical for Grand-Prix! } { [%cal Rc1g5,Rg5h6,Bf3g5,Gc4f7] }) 10. Qh4 { This is the point of White's sacrifice white will try to attack the weakened black king. Since black king is under fire for the next couple of moves black has to take critical decisions. } { [%cal Gc1h6,Rf3g5] [%clk 0:02:45] } 10... Ng6!? { A very logical reaction trying to exhange the queens. } { [%csl Rd8,Yh4][%cal Rd8h4] [%clk 0:02:45] } (10... fxe4! { This move is even better and typical way of meeting white's attack which allows black to play the very important move Nf5, for instance } { [%csl Gf5][%cal Ge7f5] } 11. Ng5 (11. dxe4 { to cover f5-square is possible } { [%csl Rf5][%cal Ge7f5,Re4f5] } 11... Ng6 12. Qh5 Nce5 $132 { but black has enough resources here as well. } { [%cal Re5f3,Bd8h4] }) 11... h6 12. Ngxe4 Nf5! $17 { Here it comes! h6-pawn is protected and black can start their play in the center. } { [%csl Rh6,Rf5,Rh4,Rd8,Gd5][%cal Gf5h6,Gd6d5] }) 11. Qh5! { White wants to attack, of course one can not exchange the queens while attacking the opponent's king. } { [%cal Rc1h6,Bf3g5] [%clk 0:02:37] } 11... Nd4? { This active move is in fact a losing mistake! The position is very sharp and only one mistake might cost the entire game and here it's the case as well. That's why a lot of anti-Sicilian lovers prefer Grand-Prix Attack, especially at faster time controls! } { [%clk 0:02:35] } (11... fxe4 12. Ng5 h6 13. Ngxe4 (13. Nxf7? { This move is in fact a blunder by white but the most popular move according to Lichess Database! } 13... Rxf7 14. Rxf7 (14. Qxg6 Ne5 $19 { Black is more than fine }) 14... Kxf7 15. Bxh6 { happened in Della Morte, German - Kropff, Ricardo, 1/2-1/2, Asuncion La Pergola Jardin, 2011 but Black missed a chance to win by } 15... Qh4! { not afraid of } 16. Rf1+ Kg8 17. Qxg6 Qxh6 18. Qf7+ Kh7 $19 { as black's king is quiet safe. }) 13... Qh4! $10 { Black is fine as in 4 other Lichess games! }) 12. exf5? { Even though not the best move, Lichess database contains 19 games with it. The point is that black now gets a chance to exchange the attacking knight on f3 with a tactical detail. } { [%clk 0:02:25] } (12. Ng5! { was a must before capturing on f5 to retain the knight and avoid Qh4 tricks. } 12... h6 13. exf5 hxg5 (13... Nxf5 { Transposes into our game! }) 14. Bxg5 Qe8 { as happened in 1 Lichess game: xcooltrainx - Chess_Navigator, 1/2-1/2 and now } 15. f6! { would win as white will crush through on the dark squares. } { [%csl Gg8][%cal Gf6g7,Rg5f6] }) 12... Nxf5 { Black could eliminate the dangerous horse on f3. } { [%clk 0:02:26] } (12... Nxf3+! 13. Rxf3? { It seems white will finish the game by checkmating the black king. } { [%cal Gf3h3,Gh3h7,Rf5g6] } (13. Qxf3 $13) 13... Qh4!! $19 { with this move black is in fact winning as white can not avoid exchange of queens as happened in 10 Lichess games. }) 13. Ng5 { White is threatening to checkmate black king and there's only one way to deal with it! } { [%csl Gh7][%cal Gh5h7] [%clk 0:02:19] } 13... h6 { With this obvious move black allows a neat finish and now we transposed back into the notes of the 12th move. } { [%clk 0:02:19] } (13... Nh6! { This move might be a better defence as white still has to prove his attack is winning. } 14. Nce4! { Stockfish shows some nice attacking ideas i'd like to share. } { [%csl Gh7][%cal Gg5h7,Re4g5] } 14... d5 15. Nxh7!! { now black needs to give up their queen. } 15... Kxh7 16. Bg5! { [%cal Ge4f6] } 16... f6 17. Rxf6 Rxf6 18. Nxf6+ Qxf6! 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Rf1! Bg7 21. Bb3 $18 { This position is winning according to Stockfish as Black king is weak and black's three minor pieces are not enough for the queen and two passers. } { [%cal Gc2c3,Gb3c2,Gd3d4,Gg2g4] }) 14. Rxf5!! { There's no way back! White has to play this move to open up the a2-g8 diagonal! A typical sacrifice for the Grand-Prix Attack as it can be found in other 14 Lichess games as well. } { [%clk 0:02:12] } 14... exf5 { [%cal Gc4g8] [%clk 0:02:12] } (14... d5 { This was tried successfully in 1 Lichess game. White player failed to attack directly as } 15. Nxf7! Rxf7 16. Rxf7 Kxf7 17. Bxh6 { gives white with a crushing attack. } { [%csl Gf7,Gg6,Gg7,Gf1][%cal Ga1f1] }) 15. Qxg6 { [%clk 0:02:10] } 15... hxg5 { [%clk 0:02:11] } 16. Bxg5 { [%csl Gd8][%cal Rg5f6] [%clk 0:02:09] } 16... Qe8 { and now last trick black came up with is to meet Bf6 with Qe3! } { [%csl Re3][%cal Gg5f6,Re8e3] [%clk 0:01:54] } 17. Ne4!! { the last finess. } { [%clk 0:01:38] } (17. Bf6?? { would be a mistake as after } 17... Qe3+ 18. Kh1 Qh6 $17 { black would be close to be winning with extra material in } { bobby_inc - Bullitzer, 0-1, -, https://lichess.org/9XL8iPfx }) 17... Kh8 { [%clk 0:00:59] } 18. Qh5+! { It's still not too late to make a mistake as } { [%clk 0:01:32] } (18. Nf6?? { was played in another lichess game } 18... fxg6 19. Nxe8 Rxe8 { actually it's black rook up and winning. } { ChessFiq14 - shadow-Tal, 0-1, -, https://lichess.org/rywR60K9 }) 18... Kg8 { [%clk 0:00:58] } 19. Nf6+ { Black resigned as mate is inevitable.
You will find further instructive examples about Grand-Prix Attack in the next chapters. } { [%clk 0:01:17] } 1-0


