{ The January 2026 edition of the Lichess Game of the Month features a solid miniature that offers some instructive positional lessons. You can join February contest via this link: https://lichess.org/@/Lichess/blog/lichess-game-of-the-month-january-26/suNJtZUH }
1. Nf3 { [%clk 0:10:00] } 1... Nf6 { [%clk 0:10:00] } 2. g3 { [%clk 0:09:58] } 2... g6 { [%clk 0:09:56] } 3. Bg2 { [%clk 0:09:57] } 3... Bg7 { [%clk 0:09:55] } 4. O-O { Once again, David Bronstein's favorite: King's Indian Attack. Bronstein advises begginers to play it in this book "Sorcerer's Apprentice". } { [%clk 0:09:57] } 4... d5 { [%clk 0:09:52] } (4... O-O 5. d3 d6 { Ljubomir Ljubojevic recalls Bobby Fischer liked to meet King's Indian Attack in following fashion } 6. c4 (6. e4 c5 { going for Sicilian Defense }) 6... e5 { or King's Indian Defense against English Opening, striving for an imbalanced position in each case. }) 5. d3 { White prefers to play in the spirit of King's Indian Attack. } { [%clk 0:09:57] } (5. d4 { would lead to Grünfeld type of positions. }) 5... O-O { [%clk 0:09:51] } 6. Nbd2 { [%cal Ge2e4] [%clk 0:09:56] } 6... c5 { [%clk 0:09:44] } 7. e4 { Tigran Petrosian excelled in these kinds of positions with both colors, and he once famously said, 'The King's Indian Defense is feeding my family.' } { [%clk 0:09:54] } 7... Nc6 { [%clk 0:09:34] } 8. c3 { White might prepare e5 and d4 with this move. } { [%csl Ge5,Gd4][%cal Re4e5,Gd3d4] [%clk 0:09:45] } 8... b6 { [%clk 0:08:35] } (8... e5 { to prevent White's next move was also possible. }) 9. e5 { I like this space-gaining move, blunting the ♗g7. } { [%clk 0:09:25] } (9. Re1 { is the most popular move in this position. }) 9... Ng4 { [%clk 0:08:23] } 10. d4 { [%clk 0:09:22] } 10... cxd4 { [%clk 0:08:07] } 11. cxd4 { [%cal Gh2h3,Gf1e1,Rd2b1,Rb1c3,Bc1f4] [%clk 0:09:22] } 11... f6! { Necessary and strong! Black is attempting to break the clamp on their position; otherwise White would slowly increase the pressure. } { [%clk 0:08:04] } 12. h3 { [%clk 0:09:18] } 12... Nh6 { [%clk 0:08:00] } 13. exf6 { [%clk 0:09:09] } (13. Re1 { I would prefer this move to capturing the pawn to see how Black proceeds. }) 13... Bxf6?! { [%csl Gd4] [%clk 0:07:44] } (13... exf6 { This natural move would keep Black's formation intact; instead, Black opts for active play against White's d4-pawn. }) 14. Nb3 { [%clk 0:08:29] } (14. Ne5! { Since Black's pieces are loose, it's not surprising that tactical opportunities exist. } 14... Nxe5 15. dxe5 Bxe5? (15... Bg7 $16 { is better. }) 16. Nc4! { [%csl Gd5,Ga8][%cal Yg2a8,Gc1h6] } 16... dxc4 17. Bxh6 $18 { [%csl Gf8,Ga8] }) 14... Nf5 { [%clk 0:07:26] } 15. Ne5 { This move is good but not as strong as on the previous move. } { [%clk 0:08:24] } 15... Bb7 { [%clk 0:07:03] } (15... Ncxd4?? 16. Nxd4 Bxe5 17. Nc6 Qd6 18. Nxe5 Qxe5 19. Qxd5+ $18) 16. Nxc6 { [%clk 0:07:19] } (16. Bf4 { Normal development would be fine as well. } 16... g5 { is not dangerous as } 17. Qg4 $14 { or } { [%csl Rg5,Rf5][%cal Gg4e6] } (17. Nxc6 Bxc6 18. Be5 $14)) 16... Bxc6 { Let's try to evaluate the position. It seems that both sides have weaknesses: White's d-pawn against Black's e-pawn and e5-square but who has the better of it? This strucutre might arise from other openings like French Tarrasch and experience shows that having the f-file Black can compensate their weaknesses by dynamic play on the kingside.
In other words, White is better statically, while Black should strive for dynamic counterplay. } { [%clk 0:07:01] } 17. g4? { White would like to remove the annoying knight pressuring the d4-pawn, but this move causes more harm by weakening f4-square than it provides benefits. } { [%clk 0:07:16] } (17. Re1 { Simple and strong, with a bind on the e5-square. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gc1f4,Ga1c1] }) 17... Nh4 { [%clk 0:06:41] } 18. Bh1 { [%clk 0:07:05] } 18... a5 { [%clk 0:06:13] } 19. Be3 { White wants to play ♘d2, but this move is blocking the very important e-file. } { [%clk 0:06:29] } (19. Bh6 { A good move gaining tempo to prepare the play on the e5-square. } 19... Rf7 20. Qd2 $10 { not allowing Black's ...g6-g5. }) 19... a4 { [%clk 0:06:04] } 20. Nd2 { [%clk 0:06:25] } 20... e6 { [%clk 0:05:57] } 21. Rc1 { [%clk 0:06:21] } 21... Bb5 { [%clk 0:05:52] } 22. Re1 { [%clk 0:06:15] } 22... Qd6 { [%clk 0:04:52] } 23. Bh6?? { A simple oversight that ends the game on the spot, but the finish is beautiful. } { [%clk 0:05:40] } (23. Nf3 Nxf3+ 24. Bxf3 Rf7 { is equal but it seems easier to play with Black pieces. } { [%cal Ga8f8] }) 23... Bxd4! { [%clk 0:04:41] } 24. Be3 { [%clk 0:05:01] } (24. Bxf8 Qg3+ 25. Bg2 Qxg2#) 24... Rxf2!! { An elegant rook sacrifice that finishes off White's king. } { [%clk 0:04:32] } (24... Bxe3 25. Rxe3 Rxf2 { is similar. }) 25. Kxf2 { [%clk 0:03:39] } 25... Qh2+ { [%clk 0:04:20] } 26. Bg2 { [%clk 0:03:27] } 26... Qxg2# { 0-1 Black wins by checkmate. } { Brilliant finish by @stormy2018. } { [%clk 0:04:18] } 0-1


