{ As a King's Indian Defense aficionado, I enjoy this game even more. While the KID might be rare in today’s elite tournaments, it remains close to my heart. Having grown up with Fischer's and Kasparov’s brilliant games and later inspired by the likes of Nakamura, Radjabov, and Ding Liren, I still employ this opening in my own games. }
1. d4 { [%clk 0:05:00] } 1... Nf6 { [%clk 0:05:00] } 2. c4 { [%clk 0:05:02] } 2... g6 { [%clk 0:05:03] } 3. Nc3 { [%clk 0:05:04] } 3... Bg7 { [%clk 0:05:06] } 4. e4 { [%clk 0:05:06] } 4... d6 { [%clk 0:05:09] } (4... O-O { I recall the famous Letelier - Fischer game from 1960, which you can find in the next chapter, even though the move order doesn't change much if White continues as in our game. }) 5. Nf3 { [%clk 0:05:08] } 5... O-O { [%clk 0:05:11] } (5... Bg4!? { A modern line that has recently become popular, featuring a logical idea often found in similar structures. } 6. Be2 Bxf3 7. Bxf3 e5 8. d5 h5! { This is the point of delaying castling as Black intends to exchange the dark squared bishop. A very instructive game inspired me to take up this variation myself last year: } { Krstulovic, Alex - Nenezic, M., 0-1, TCh-SRB Premier 2023, https://lichess.org/yEB01BaR } { [%cal Gg7h6] }) 6. Be2 { [%clk 0:05:11] } 6... e5 { [%clk 0:05:14] } 7. O-O { [%clk 0:05:13] } 7... Nc6 { Since it is thought that White has a pleasant position in the main lines of Mar del Plata variation, Grandmasters have tried different ideas in this old line. } { [%clk 0:05:15] } (7... h6!? { A useful move "preventing" 8.♗e3 due to 8...♘g4, while also vacating h7-square. } 8. Re1 Nbd7 9. Bf1 Nh7!? { preparing ...♘g5. } { [%csl Gg5][%cal Gh7g5] }) (7... Bg4!? { Caruana revived this line a while ago with the following idea: } 8. Be3 Bxf3 9. Bxf3 exd4 10. Bxd4 Nc6 11. Be3 Re8 12. Qd2 Nd7 13. Rad1 Bxc3! { White's bishops and space advantage did not promise an edge in the game due to Black's active piece play on the dark squares. } { Wojtaszek, R.. - Caruana, F.., 0-1, 83rd Tata Steel Masters, 2021, https://lichess.org/sKHnUdfN }) (7... b6!? { Another useful move waiting for White to show their cards—not to mention the respectable main lines 7...exd4 and 7...♘a6. }) 8. d5 { After this push, the battleground is divided into two halves. White will play on the queenside, and Black will strive for a checkmating attack! } { [%clk 0:05:16] } 8... Ne7 { [%clk 0:05:17] } 9. b4 { Bayonet Attack is the most direct way of attacking the KID. } { [%clk 0:05:18] } 9... Ne8 { [%clk 0:05:18] } (9... a5 { Looks like the principal decision to "punish" White, but in general, first player is happy to open lines on the queenside. }) (9... Nd7 { is another route for the knight to control c5-square. }) 10. c5 { White's play can take a few directions. One is to open the c-file directly with cxd6 and target the d6 pawn; second is to attack the base of the pawn chain by preparing b5-b6. White can also try playing c5-c6 to gain more space and create targets. } { [%clk 0:05:21] } 10... f5 { Black starts their play on the kingside. Unlike White, Black's play consists of a direct attack on the opponent's king. } { [%clk 0:05:21] } 11. Nd2 { [%cal Gd2c4] [%clk 0:05:22] } 11... Bh6!? { Black uses the moment to exchange their "bad" bishop, though they lose some time in doing so. } { [%clk 0:05:18] } 12. Nc4 { [%clk 0:05:22] } 12... Bxc1 { [%clk 0:05:19] } 13. Rxc1 { [%clk 0:05:25] } 13... f4 { It's considered dubious to allow ♗g4 in these type of positions letting White exchange their own bad bishop, but similar to 11...♗h6 this move would also cost White time. } { [%clk 0:05:18] } (13... fxe4 14. Nxe4 Nf5 { Black could open the f-file and use the d4-square, but they chose the traditional pawn storm instead. } { [%cal Gf5d4] }) 14. a4 { [%clk 0:05:23] } (14. Bg4! { A very solid option here to exchange Black's mighty bishop. }) 14... g5 { [%clk 0:05:21] } 15. cxd6 { White goes for direct play on the c-file. However, White could have waited a bit longer before exchanging. } { [%clk 0:05:24] } (15. b5 { A more flexible way to continue the attack. } { [%cal Gc5c6,Gb5b6] } 15... Ng6 (15... dxc5?? 16. Nxe5 $18) 16. c6!? { This is a completely different approach to play against the opponent's light-squared bishop. Later white's king can find a safe heaven in the center via f2-e1-d2 after f2-f3. } { [%cal Ga4a5] }) (15. Bg4!? { is still possible. }) 15... cxd6 { [%clk 0:05:22] } 16. Nb5 { White provokes ...a6 to create weakness on the b6-square. } { [%clk 0:05:27] } (16. Bg4 { Would still be a good idea. Black's most powerful attacking piece is often the light-squared bishop as we shall see in the game. }) 16... Ng6 { Black ignores white's knight jump. } { [%clk 0:05:24] } (16... a6 17. Nc3 $40 { [%cal Ga4a5,Gc3a4,Ga4b6] }) 17. a5 { [%clk 0:05:26] } 17... Qe7 { [%clk 0:05:24] } 18. a6?! { White decides to sacrifice a pawn to weaken the c6-square. } { [%clk 0:05:14] } (18. Nd2 { Threatening ♘xa7 with a possible invasion on the c7 looked better. } { [%csl Ga7,Gc7,Ra8,Rc8][%cal Gb5a7] }) 18... bxa6 { [%clk 0:05:25] } 19. Nc3 { [%clk 0:05:10] } 19... Rf7 { A typical device to strengthen the defence of the 7th rank. } { [%clk 0:05:24] } 20. Na5 { [%clk 0:05:09] } 20... Bd7 { [%clk 0:05:19] } 21. Nc6 { [%clk 0:05:10] } 21... Qf6! { Of course, it would be disastrous to take the apparently strong knight. } { [%clk 0:05:13] } (21... Bxc6?? 22. dxc6 $18 { [%csl Gc4,Gd5][%cal Ge2c4,Gc3d5] }) 22. f3? { The first critical mistake of the game! By blocking the d1-h5 diagonal, Black's attack gains momentum and the f3-pawn becomes a "hook". } { [%clk 0:05:07] } (22. Bxa6 { [%csl Gb7][%cal Ga6b7] } 22... h5! { Another pawn sacrifice to open the lines against white's king. } { [%cal Ba6b7,Rd7g4,Gf7b7] } 23. Qxh5? Rh7 24. Qd1 g4 { Black has a crushing attack! } { [%cal Gf6h4] }) (22. Ra1! { A very useful attacking move after which White could have kept the balance, for instance; } 22... Nc7 23. Bg4 Bxg4 24. Qxg4 Raf8 25. Qf5 { It is always a big relief for White to exchange the queens. } 25... Qxf5 26. exf5 Nh4 27. f6 $10 { [%cal Gc3e4] }) 22... h5 { [%clk 0:05:14] } (22... g4! { Black could sacrifice a pawn similarly to their opponent, for example: } 23. fxg4 Qg5 { [%cal Ge8f6,Gh7h5] } 24. h3 Nf6 25. Bf3 h5 26. gxh5 Nh4 { Black's heavy artillery can use the g-file with great effect. } { [%cal Gd7h3] }) 23. Bxa6 { White is threatening to trap the rook with ♗b7... } { [%clk 0:04:35] } 23... g4!! { ...Black ignores the thtreat. } { [%clk 0:05:02] } 24. Bb7 { [%clk 0:04:31] } 24... g3! { This is the point, of course! This position reminds me of the famous Piket - Kasparov game, which can also be found in this study. } { [%clk 0:04:58] } 25. Bxa8 { [%clk 0:04:30] } 25... Qh4 { [%clk 0:05:00] } (25... gxh2+?? { Of course, this would be a big mistake, since White can use Black's pawn as a shelter after } 26. Kh1! $18 { and the attack is over. }) 26. h3 { [%clk 0:04:31] } 26... Bxh3! { This is why light-squared bishop is so valuable in this line, again, reminiscent of Piket - Kasparov. } { [%clk 0:05:02] } 27. gxh3 { [%clk 0:04:31] } 27... Qxh3 { Despite being a rook down, Black has a devastating attack. } { [%clk 0:05:04] } 28. Qe2 { White is threatening to play ♕g2, so... } { [%cal Ge2g2] [%clk 0:04:34] } 28... Nh4! { Now Black has an unstoppable threat of playing g3-g2. } { [%clk 0:05:06] } 29. Rc2 { [%clk 0:04:31] } 29... Rg7! { Renewing the threat. Against the tempting } { [%cal Gg3g2] [%clk 0:04:46] } (29... g2?! 30. Qxg2+! Nxg2 31. Rxg2+ { White has enough pieces against the queen, so Black needs to be precise after the hasty pawn 29...g2. }) 30. Qg2 { White has no way to survive, so they decided to sacrifice the queen. } { [%clk 0:04:15] } 30... Nxg2 { [%clk 0:04:46] } 31. Rxg2 { White has a rook and two minor pieces against the queen and two pawns for the moment... } { [%clk 0:04:18] } 31... Qc8! $19 { Even without this move, Black's passers on the kingside and white's weak king would decide the outcome, but now it's completely over. } { [%csl Gh5,Gg3,Ga8] [%clk 0:04:47] } 32. b5 { [%clk 0:04:07] } 32... Qxa8 { [%clk 0:04:45] } 33. Ra1 { [%clk 0:04:10] } 33... h4 { [%clk 0:04:43] } 34. b6 { [%clk 0:04:10] } 34... h3 { [%clk 0:04:41] } 35. bxa7 { [%clk 0:04:01] } (35. Rb2 { It's still lost, but there might be some practical difficulties due to the threats of bxa7 or ♖xa7 in this case. Black should buy some time and continue the attack on the opponent's king, for instance: } { [%cal Gb6b7,Gb6a7] } 35... a6 36. Rba2 Qc8 37. Rxa6 h2+ 38. Kh1 Qh3 $19) 35... hxg2 { [%clk 0:04:37] } 36. Nb5 { [%clk 0:03:57] } 36... Nc7 { [%clk 0:04:35] } 37. Nxc7 { Otherwise the knight will control the queening square. } { [%clk 0:03:55] } (37. Nxd6 Qf8 { [%cal Gf8c5,Gc5g1] } 38. Nb7 Qc8 $19 { [%cal Gc8h3] }) 37... Rxc7 { [%clk 0:04:38] } 38. Rb1 { [%clk 0:03:57] } 38... Rxa7 { The simplest solution is to sacrifice the queen. } { [%clk 0:04:38] } 39. Rb8+ { [%clk 0:03:57] } 39... Qxb8 { [%clk 0:04:40] } 40. Nxb8 { [%clk 0:04:00] } 40... Ra2 { Black is exchange and two pawns up after all. } { [%clk 0:04:37] } 41. Nc6 { [%clk 0:04:01] } 41... Rf2 { [%clk 0:04:32] } 42. Ne7+ { [%clk 0:03:55] } 42... Kf7 { [%clk 0:04:34] } 43. Ng6 { Last stalemate trick! } { [%clk 0:03:54] } 43... Rf1+ { [%clk 0:04:32] } (43... Kxg6 { Stalemate! }) 44. Kxg2 { [%clk 0:03:56] } 44... Kxg6 { [%clk 0:04:35] } (44... Rf2+ 45. Kg1 Kxg6 $19) 45. Kxf1 { [%clk 0:03:57] } 45... Kf7 { [%clk 0:04:38] } 46. Kg2 { [%clk 0:03:53] } 46... Ke7 { [%clk 0:04:20] } 47. Kf1 { [%clk 0:03:55] } 47... Kd7 { [%clk 0:04:23] } 48. Ke2 { [%clk 0:03:58] } 48... Kc7 { [%clk 0:04:26] } 49. Ke1 { [%clk 0:04:00] } 49... Kb6 { [%clk 0:04:28] } 50. Ke2 { [%clk 0:04:03] } 50... Kc5 { [%clk 0:04:30] } 51. Ke1 { [%clk 0:04:06] } 51... Kd4 { [%clk 0:04:32] } 52. Ke2 { [%clk 0:04:08] } 52... g2 { [%clk 0:04:32] } 53. Kf2 { [%clk 0:04:10] } 53... g1=Q+ { [%clk 0:04:34] } 54. Kxg1 { [%clk 0:04:12] } 54... Ke3 { [%clk 0:04:37] } 55. Kg2 { [%clk 0:04:15] } 55... Ke2 { 0-1 White resigns. } { [%clk 0:04:40] } 0-1


