{ In Lichess October Game Of The Month, we have a lovely kingisde attack starting with a nice exchange sacrifice. Even though it's an attacking game, it reminded me of a well known strategical concept stated by Siegbert Tarrasch "If one piece is badly placed, your whole game is bad." Enjoy! }
1. g3 { A very flexible first move hiding the intentions of the first player. } { [%clk 0:10:00] } 1... d5 { [%clk 0:10:00] } 2. Bg2 { [%clk 0:09:59] } 2... c6 { Black immeadiately starts fighting against the opponent's light-squared bishop by building a pawn wall. } { [%clk 0:09:59] } 3. d4 { White has now transposed the game into a Catalan Opening which was "invented" by Savielly Tartakower in the 1929 Barcelona tournament! Further information is here: https://lichess.org/opening/Catalan_Opening } { [%clk 0:09:57] } 3... Nf6 { [%clk 0:09:56] } 4. Nf3 { [%clk 0:09:55] } 4... h6 { Black is apparently preparing to play ...Bf5 and then ...e6 without the bishop getting harrased by Nh4. } { [%cal Gc8f5,Re7e6,Yf3h4,Bf5h7] [%clk 0:09:54] } (4... Bf5 { is the most popular move here. } 5. c4 e6 6. Nc3 h6 { etc. }) 5. O-O { [%clk 0:09:54] } 5... e6?! { This move is inconsistent with the previous move. We can consider 4...h6 a loss of time, as controlling the g5-square was not urgent. } { [%clk 0:09:52] } 6. c3 { [%cal Rb1d2,Bf1e1,Ge2e4] [%clk 0:09:53] } (6. c4 { It was also possible to play in the classical Catalan spirit , but I like White's idea of preparing to open up the center. }) 6... Bd6 { Black continues developing actively and normally, but since White is about tobreak open the center with the move e2-e4 next, Black needs to consider of how to meet the opponent's idea.
In view of 12...Be7, Black will eventually retreat the bishop to e7. It was wiser to play, } { [%clk 0:09:50] } (6... Be7 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. Re1 c5 9. e4 { This move no longer comes with the threat of e4-e5, allowing Black to play } 9... cxd4! { with the idea of } 10. e5?! (10. Nxd4 { would be better. }) 10... dxc3! 11. exf6? cxd2 $19 { [%csl Ge1][%cal Gd2e1] }) 7. Nbd2 { [%clk 0:09:51] } 7... O-O { [%clk 0:09:49] } 8. Re1 { [%clk 0:09:50] } 8... Nbd7 { [%clk 0:09:47] } 9. e4 { The moment has come! White claims the center and Black faces the real problem: the light-squared bishop! Unfortunately we never see that piece move in this game.
It's instructive to note that if Black had now ...Re8 instead of 4...h6 on the board, they could now play 9...e5. } { [%cal Ge4e5] [%clk 0:09:49] } 9... dxe4 { Black has almost no choice but to take the pawn, otherwise 10.e5 would follow. } { [%clk 0:09:45] } (9... e5? { can not be played. } 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. exd5 $18 { [%cal Ge1e5] }) 10. Nxe4 { [%clk 0:09:49] } 10... Nxe4 { [%clk 0:09:44] } 11. Rxe4 { Let's stop for a moment and clarify the situation. White has gained central superiority with the previous operation. Black needs to accomplish two things:
1. Counterattack in the center with either ...e5 or ...c5
2. Develop the light-squared bishop and in the meantime take care of the opponent's kingside attack! } { [%clk 0:09:49] } 11... Nf6 { It's hard to do without this move but it also sends White's rook where it wants to go. } { [%clk 0:09:42] } (11... c5 { keeping the d8-h4 diagonal open to meet Rh4 with Be7 would be nicer. } 12. Rh4 (12. dxc5 Bxc5 (12... Nxc5? 13. Rd4 $18) 13. Qe2 $14 { Black still has to develop the queenside. }) 12... Be7! 13. Rh5 cxd4 $10 { [%cal Gd7f6] }) 12. Rh4 { [%clk 0:09:47] } 12... Be7 { [%clk 0:09:32] } 13. Ne5 { Paving the way for White's queen, but this move, however, presents a chance to exchange that annoying knight for Black. } { [%clk 0:09:39] } 13... Nh7? { I think this is the most critical moment for Black during the whole game. Black keeps the knight around their king but there was a better and instructive retreat. } { [%cal Ge7h4] [%clk 0:09:22] } (13... Nd7! { Exchanging the opponent's attacking pieces is always a good defensive strategy. } { [%cal Gd7e5,Re7h4] } 14. Nxd7 Bxd7 (14... Bxh4? { Black can not exchange more pieces for tactical reasons, } 15. Nxf8 Bf6 16. Nxe6 $16 { wins a pawn. } (16. Ng6 $16 { is even better according to Stockfish. })) 15. Rh5 $14 { As the knights went off the board, White's attack lost some of its dynamics. }) 14. Rg4 { [%csl Gh6][%cal Gc1h6] [%clk 0:09:14] } 14... Nf6 { Allowing White to start a decisive attack. Better defence was } { [%clk 0:08:58] } (14... Bg5 15. Bxg5 Nxg5 16. h4 Nh7 $16) 15. Bxh6! { Rather natural exchange sacrifice! Black lost too much time with their pieces, and Bc8 is still out of the game. } { [%clk 0:09:11] } 15... Nxg4 { [%clk 0:08:56] } 16. Qxg4 { [%csl Gg7][%cal Gg4g7] [%clk 0:09:11] } 16... Bf6 { [%clk 0:08:47] } 17. Be4 { Preparing Qh5 with deadly consequences, which Black cannot prevent. } { [%csl Gh5][%cal Rg4h5] [%clk 0:09:01] } 17... Re8 { [%clk 0:08:40] } (17... Bd7 { One instructive variation runs: } 18. Qh5 Bxe5 19. Bh7+! Kxh7 (19... Kh8 20. Be3 $18 (20. Bg5? Qxg5 $18 { This is not the ideal way to win because White loses too much material. })) 20. Bg5+ Kg8 21. Bxd8 $18) 18. Qh5 { [%csl Gf7,Ge5][%cal Gh5f7,Ge4h7] [%clk 0:08:44] } 18... Bxe5 { Black has to give up one more defender of their king; now the g7-square is also weakened. } { [%clk 0:08:18] } 19. dxe5 { Qg4 and Bg5 are the immeadiate, deadly threats. } { [%csl Gg4,Rg5,Yg7,Bh7][%cal Gh5g4,Rh6g5] [%clk 0:08:31] } 19... gxh6 { Black has no defence. } { [%clk 0:08:15] } (19... Qc7 20. Qg5 f5 (20... g6 21. Qf6 $18) 21. exf6! { The en passant rule wins the game. }) 20. Qxh6 { White has a decisive attack and has a well-known mate-in-four threat to begin with. } { [%clk 0:08:26] } 20... f5 { [%clk 0:07:39] } (20... a6 { to illustrate of White's threat. } 21. Bh7+! Kh8 22. Bg6+ Kg8 23. Qh7+ Kf8 24. Qxf7#) (20... Qc7 21. Bh7+ Kh8 22. Bc2+ { Stockfish clears the e-file for the rook. } 22... Kg8 23. Re1 { [%cal Ge1e4] } 23... f5 24. exf6 $18 { It's mate in #8 according to Stockfish. } { [%cal Ge1e4,Ge4e5] }) 21. exf6! { One more time en passant rule came to rescue. It is the only move wins the game. The Black king has no defence. } { [%clk 0:08:05] } 21... Qd7 { Black's playing without their queenside pieces whole game thus White has all the time to bring their rook into play as well. } { [%clk 0:07:35] } 22. Qg6+ { [%clk 0:07:53] } 22... Kf8 { [%clk 0:07:33] } 23. Qh5 { [%clk 0:07:05] } 23... Qf7 { [%clk 0:07:29] } 24. Qh8+ { [%clk 0:06:52] } 24... Qg8 { [%clk 0:07:26] } 25. Qh6+ { [%clk 0:06:45] } 25... Kf7 { [%clk 0:07:22] } 26. Re1 { Of course, it's hard for a human to win the as cleanly as Stockish does, but White is up to the task here. } { [%clk 0:05:58] } (26. Bf3 { is the neat Stockfish solution to finish the game. } { [%cal Gf3h5] } 26... e5 (26... Qh8 27. Bh5+ Kg8 28. f7#) 27. Bh5+ Ke6 28. f7+ $18) 26... e5 { ...and Black was hoping to develop their bishop. } { [%clk 0:07:19] } 27. Bh7! { or not! Black must now deal with the deadly attack against their king! } { [%clk 0:05:44] } 27... Qf8 { [%clk 0:07:01] } 28. Qg6+ { [%clk 0:05:41] } 28... Ke6 { [%clk 0:06:55] } 29. f7+ { [%clk 0:05:38] } 29... Ke7 { [%clk 0:06:48] } 30. Rxe5+ { [%clk 0:05:36] } 30... Kd8 { [%clk 0:06:44] } 31. Rxe8+ { 1-0 Black resigns. } { A nice attacking game by @Panikin_Skywalker! } { [%clk 0:05:33] } 1-0


