{ Almost every chess player likes sacrifical attacks against opponent king. To master the art of attack one should study typical sacrifices. In 2025 June Game Of The Month we'll witness typical attack with sacrifices develop and lead to checkmate. }
1. e4 { [%clk 0:30:00] } 1... c5 { [%clk 0:30:00] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 0:29:57] } 2... e6 { [%clk 0:29:55] } 3. d4 { [%clk 0:29:52] } 3... cxd4 { [%clk 0:29:50] } 4. c3 { An interesting move order to invite black so-called Smith-Morra Gambit. } { [%clk 0:29:49] } (4. Nxd4 { is the main line. }) (4. Qxd4 { an interesting sideline gained some popularity in recent years. }) 4... Nf6 { Black decides to play solidly and transposed the game into the Alapin Variation of the Sicilian Defense. } { [%clk 0:29:42] } (4... dxc3 { Theory considers the proof of the pudding is in the eating, but there's nothing wrong with the game continuation as well. }) (4... d5 { Another transposition to one of the main lines of the Alapin Sicilian. }) 5. e5 { [%clk 0:29:40] } 5... Nd5 { [%clk 0:29:33] } 6. cxd4 { A very well-known position in the Alapin variation of Sicilian Defense. Even though Alapin Variation is considered to be solid, it can also be used by attacking players as the e5-pawn provides a king-side space advantage or isolated queen's pawn gives white attacking chances for white. } { [%clk 0:29:32] } 6... d6 { [%clk 0:29:25] } 7. Nc3 { [%clk 0:28:52] } (7. a3!? { This move with the idea of playing Bd3 is one of the weapons that made Divya Deshmukh the winner of 2025 Fide Women's World Cup! She used this move to beat former world champion GM Tan Zhongyi in the semi-finals. } { [%cal Gf1d3] }) (7. Bc4 { By far the main move, even though light-squared bishop belongs to b1-h7 diagonal after 7.Bd3 black can disturb white's bishop on that square. }) (7. Bd3 { After this logical move, apart from other methods, black can simplify the position by means of } 7... dxe5 8. dxe5 (8. Nxe5 { White might seek their attacking chances with the Isolated Queen's Pawn, but black is still very solid. }) 8... Nb4 $10) 7... Nxc3 { [%clk 0:29:16] } 8. bxc3 { As a result of the exchange initiated by 7.Nc3 white strengthened the center by bringing another pawn closer to the center, but white also has a weak pawn on the semi-open c-file. This means white has to attack to compansate their weaknesses by using their better control over the central squares. } { [%clk 0:28:52] } 8... Qc7 { [%cal Gc7c3] [%clk 0:29:08] } 9. Qb3 { [%clk 0:28:44] } 9... Nd7 { [%csl Ge5] [%clk 0:28:28] } 10. Bf4 { [%clk 0:28:26] } 10... Be7 { With the hindsight it's also possible to start with } { [%clk 0:27:15] } (10... dxe5 11. Nxe5 Bd6 { not to loose a tempo with Be7-Bd6 as in the game. }) 11. Bd3 { White's pieces are actively placed for a possible attacking scenario. That's why aggresive players would like to play Alapin as well. } { [%clk 0:27:38] } 11... O-O { [%clk 0:26:21] } 12. O-O { Both sides made logical moves to complete their development. Black needs to exchange pieces to make use of white's weaknesses in the endgame. In the meantime white will seek active play on the kingside or push their c and d-pawns to create a passed pawn or increase the pressure. } { [%clk 0:26:40] } 12... dxe5 { [%clk 0:25:51] } 13. Nxe5 { [%clk 0:26:05] } (13. dxe5 { Unfortunately White can not keep more pieces by this move. } 13... Nc5 $15 { [%csl Gb3,Gd3][%cal Gc5d3,Gc5b3] }) 13... Nxe5 { [%clk 0:25:35] } 14. Bxe5 { [%clk 0:26:05] } (14. dxe5 { Keeping the bishops would please black more than white as white's stucture is even worse now and no attack yet to appear on the horizon. } 14... Bd7 $15 { Black should be better with an acitve play on the c and d-files. } { [%cal Gf8d8,Ga8c8,Gd7c6] }) 14... Bd6 { [%clk 0:25:05] } 15. Rfe1 { [%clk 0:25:51] } (15. f4 $40 { planning to use rook on the f-file would be more aggresive. } { [%cal Gf1f3,Yf4e5,Gd6e5] }) 15... Bxe5 { As mentioned on the 12th move black is well adviced to exchange pieces but they have to be careful not to further activate white's forces in doing so. } { [%clk 0:24:21] } (15... b6 { would be better to develop the queenside. } { [%csl Gb7][%cal Gc8b7] }) 16. Rxe5 { [%clk 0:25:51] } 16... b6 { [%clk 0:22:58] } 17. Rae1 { [%clk 0:23:44] } 17... Bb7 { [%clk 0:22:31] } 18. c4 { Up to this point everything went according to plan for both sides. White seeks activity by all means preparing d4-d5 with their hanging pawns formation and clears the 3rd rank for a possible kingside attack with their queen. Black is trying to develop and target the hanging pawns, but does white have an immeadiate threat? } { [%csl Rc4,Rd4] [%clk 0:22:59] } 18... Rfd8? { and only 1 mistake will cost black the game, so how can such a logical move loose the game on the spot? As mentioned above, with the last move white introduced the ideas of d4-d5 and more importantly 18.c4 clears the third rank for the queen and everything is ready very well-known Bxh7 (Greek gift) sacrifice. If you've seen this kind of sacrifices with experience it's becomes rather obvious to you, if you're less experienced you need to realize black has no defenders apart from pawn cover and white's forces are actively placed. These factors made a possible sacrifice against the black king very dangerous if not winning immediately. } { [%clk 0:20:21] } (18... Rad8 { How about Bxh7 now? } 19. Bxh7+ (19. d5! $40 exd5?? 20. Bxh7+ { Yet again! } 20... Kxh7 21. Qh3+ Kg8 22. Rh5 { white mates shortly as the open e-file eases the king hunt. There are better defensive moves of course: }) 19... Kxh7 20. Qh3+ Kg8 21. Rh5 f5 { but it only leads to a bizarre equality according to Stockfish after the forced line: } 22. Rh8+ Kf7 23. Qh5+ Ke7 24. Qg6 { [%cal Gg6e6,Gg6g7] } 24... Rxh8 25. Qxg7+ Kd6 26. Rxe6+ Kxe6 27. Qxc7 Rxd4 { [%cal Gd4d1] } 28. f4! { and this forced line might continue } { [%csl Ge5,Gc7,Gb7][%cal Gc7e5,Gc7b7] } 28... Rhd8 29. Qxb7 Rd1+ 30. Kf2 R1d2+ 31. Kg3 Rg8+ 32. Kf3 Rgd8 { and black keeps white king at bay and the position is equal.
In this instance white should calculate all the way through if there's a forced win for them, so deep calculation is required. It's not enough to be well-equipped with typical sacrifical methods, calculation is vital as well. If you can not see a clear win you can also go for another method of play which is 19.d5!, also a typical device for hanging pawn positions after which Bxh7 will become even more powerful! }) (18... g6 { blocks the light squared bishop and now white can try h4-h5 or go for the same d4-d5 plan. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5,Gd4d5] }) (18... h6 { In this case white can try bishop and queen battery with Bc2-Qd3 to create further weaknesses on the kingside in combination with d4-d5 push. } { [%csl Gh6,Gg7,Gf7,Gg8][%cal Gd3c2,Gb3d3] }) 19. Bxh7+!! { This typical yet very impressive sacrifice works due to white's very well placed heavy pieces and central control combined with black's lonely king! } { [%clk 0:19:19] } 19... Kxh7 { [%clk 0:19:06] } 20. Qh3+ { [%clk 0:18:40] } (20. Rh5+ { would allow } 20... Kg6! { and black can hold. } 21. Qh3 { [%csl Gg4][%cal Gh3g4] } 21... Rxd4 $19) 20... Kg8 { [%clk 0:18:49] } (20... Kg6 { doesn't work this time due to } 21. Qh5+ Kf6 22. Qg5#) 21. Rh5 { [%clk 0:18:24] } 21... Kf8 { [%clk 0:17:37] } (21... f5 { The same move as in the analysis of 18...Rad8 would be a better try. } 22. d5! $18 { The same method! Trying to open up the e-file to keep black king in the mating net and also d-pawn becomes an attacking power with this move! } { [%cal Ge1e7,Gd5e6] } (22. Rh8+ { This forced line is also winning. The following sequence is all forced. If you need a training position to play against computer, this one is a very good one in my opinion. You can click on the circle next to the opening explorer below to pratice.
SPOILER ALERT for the next moves! } 22... Kf7 23. Qh5+ Ke7 24. Qg6 Rxh8 25. Qxg7+ Kd8 (25... Kd6 26. Qe5+ Kd7 (26... Kc6 27. d5+ Kd7 28. Qxe6+ Kd8 29. Qf6+) 27. Qxe6+ Kd8 28. Qf6+ Kc8 (28... Kd7 29. Re7+ Kc8 30. Qxh8+ Qd8 31. Re8) 29. Qxh8+ Kd7 30. Qg7+ Kc6 31. d5+ Kd6 32. Re6+ $18) 26. Qxh8+ Kd7 27. Qg7+ Kc8 28. Qg8+ Qd8 29. Qxe6+ Kb8 30. Qe5+ Qc7 31. Qe8+ Qc8 32. Qf7 $18 { Black is paralyzed and white is attacking without material deficit. } { [%csl Ge7,Ge8][%cal Ge1e8] })) 22. Rxe6!! { Only winning move! White should not let black king find safe room in the center. We're witnessing another typical sacrifice. } { [%cal Gh5h8] [%clk 0:18:21] } 22... fxe6 { [%clk 0:16:35] } (22... f6 23. Rxf6+ gxf6 24. Rh8+ Ke7 25. Rh7+ $18) 23. Qxe6 { White's remaining forces are enough to checkmate the black king. } { [%csl Gf5,Gh8][%cal Gh5h8,Gh5f5] [%clk 0:18:21] } 23... g6 { [%clk 0:14:41] } 24. Qf6+! { [%clk 0:15:39] } 24... Ke8 { [%clk 0:13:09] } 25. Qxg6+ { [%clk 0:15:24] } 25... Kd7 { [%clk 0:11:05] } (25... Qf7 { would not defend but white has to find the precise way to finish off the black king. } 26. Re5+ Kf8 27. Qh6+ { [%cal Gf8g8,Ge5g5] } 27... Qg7 28. Rf5+ Kg8 29. Qe6+ Kh8 30. Rh5+ Qh7 31. Qf6+ Kg8 32. Rg5+ { and mates next move. }) 26. Qf5+! { Another nice move indicating black's poorly coordinated pieces. Black king can not hide and white will checkmate shortly. } { [%clk 0:15:15] } 26... Kc6 { [%clk 0:08:56] } 27. Qb5+ { [%clk 0:14:13] } 27... Kd6 { [%clk 0:08:39] } 28. Rh6+ { [%clk 0:13:57] } 28... Ke7 { [%clk 0:08:10] } 29. Qg5+ { [%clk 0:13:18] } 29... Kd7 { [%clk 0:07:51] } 30. Qg4+ { [%clk 0:12:25] } 30... Ke8 { [%clk 0:07:27] } 31. Qg8+ { [%clk 0:12:21] } 31... Ke7 { [%clk 0:07:07] } 32. Qg7+ { [%clk 0:12:16] } 32... Ke8 { [%clk 0:06:52] } 33. Rh8# { 1-0 White wins by checkmate. } { and impressive performance by @RejectedQuadratic! } { [%cal Gh8e8] [%clk 0:12:16] } 1-0


