{ Another "Capablanca bishop" game in which great Cuban shows how to play when one of the opponent's pieces is out of play by playing on the side of the board where he's essentially piece up. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Bb4 5. O-O O-O 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. d3 Bd6 8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 c5 10. Nd5 g5 11. Nxf6+ Qxf6 12. Bg3 Bg4 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Qxf3 15. gxf3 f6 16. Kg2 { This is the starting position! Black starts playing on the queenside where white's bishop doesn't take part in the game. } 16... a5 17. a4 Kf7 18. Rh1 Ke6 19. h4 Rfb8 20. hxg5 hxg5 21. b3 c6 { [%cal Gb7b5] } 22. Ra2 b5 23. Rha1 c4!! 24. axb5 cxb3 25. cxb3 Rxb5 { Black managed to open up the queenside where he's a piece up hence winning the game. } 26. Ra4 Rxb3 27. d4 Rb5 28. Rc4 Rb4 29. Rxc6 Rxd4 { 0-1 Black wins. } 0-1


