{ Now there are 2 examples by Carlsen using the space advantage to restrict the opponent's forces. }
23... Nd5 { [%csl Gg4,Gf1][%cal Gd5e3] } 24. f5! (24. Bxd5 Rxd5 25. f5 { would do the job as well. } { [%cal Gf5f6] }) 24... Ne3 25. Qf3 Nxf5 26. Nxf5 Bxf5 27. d5! { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gd5d6] } 27... Bb6 { [#] [%cal Gc5c4,Gb6g1] } 28. Bc4! { Using the pieces to restrict the opponent's forces as well. } { [%csl Gb6] } 28... Kg8 (28... exd5 29. Qxf5 dxc4 30. e6 f6 31. Bxf6 gxf6 32. Qg6) 29. d6 Qh4 { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gh4c4] } 30. b3 Rd7 31. Qe2 Qg4 { This is questionable according to Stockfish as we'll see. } 32. Rxf5!! { Very strong exchange sacrifice! } 32... Qxf5 (32... Qxe2 33. Bxe2 exf5 (33... c4+ 34. Rf2) 34. Bb5 Rd8 35. Bc4 Kf8 36. Rf1 { Domination would go on. }) 33. Rf1 Qg5 34. Bd2 Qd8 35. Qg4 { Black is exchange up but their pieces are tightly packed. } (35. Bb5 { is also possible but Carlsen is not interested in taking back the sacrificed material. } { [%csl Gd7] }) 35... a6 36. Rxf7!! { Rook sacrifice this time! } 36... Kxf7 (36... Rxf7 37. Qxe6 Qf8 38. d7 Bd8 39. Qe8 { [%cal Gc4f7] } 39... Kh7 40. Bxf7) 37. Qxe6+ Kf8 38. Qf5+ Ke8 39. Qg6+ Kf8 40. Qf5+ Ke8 41. Qg6+ Kf8 42. e6 Qf6 43. exd7 Qxg6 44. hxg6 Bd8 45. Be6 { Game ends with complete domination, black can not move! } { [%csl Gh8,Gd8,Gf8,Gd7,Gd6,Gg6] } 45... h5 46. Kf2 h4 { [%cal Gh8h5,Gh5d5] } 47. Bg4! { [%csl Gh5][%cal Gg4h5,Gh8h5] } 47... b5 48. Kf3 b4 49. axb4 cxb4 { 1-0 White wins. } { Black resigned as Black is in zugzwang and white has many ways to win. One is the bring the king to f5 and Bg5. } { [%cal Gf3e4,Ge4f5,Gd2g5] } 1-0


