24. Bb4! { This creates a transition to the knight endgame which is favorable for white. } (24. Nxc5 Bxc5 { White has to stick to the defence of the b-pawn. }) 24... Nxa6 25. Bxd6+ Ke8 26. Bxb8 Nxb8 27. Nc5! Nd7 28. b7! Nb8 { [%cal Ge8d7,Gd7c7,Gc7b6] } 29. Kf1! Kd8 30. Ke2 Kc7 31. Kd3 Kb6 32. Kd4 { Just in time. Now it's time to create a weakness on the kingside. } 32... g6 33. g4! Kb5 34. h4 { There are other moves as well with the same idea. } 34... h6?! 35. h5 gxh5 36. gxh5 { Weakness is created and fixed. Now white has to create a breakthrough to reach the weaknesses on the kingside, namely f7 and h6 pawn! } { [%csl Gh6] } 36... Ka5 37. f4 Kb6 38. e4 { f5 is a threat now! } { [%cal Gf4f5] } 38... dxe4 39. Nxe4 { White gives up the b-pawn for good reason. } 39... c5+ 40. Kc4 Kxb7 41. Nd6+ Kc6 42. Nxf7 { Black resigned as the h6-pawn is falling and the remaining black pawns will drop as well. } 1-0


