1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 { One big expert in this line is English GM Gawain Jones who had also written a book on the Grand-Prix Attack. } 2... d6 3. f4 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bc4 Nc6 6. O-O e6 7. d3 Nge7 8. Qe1 O-O 9. f5 { Up to this point we are on the familiar grounds. } 9... d5 { [%csl Gc4] } 10. Bb3 dxe4 11. dxe4 gxf5 12. Qh4 Nd4 13. Bg5 Nxf3+ (13... f6 { is better according to Stockfish as after the game continuation the rook will join the attack with tempo. }) 14. Rxf3 Qd4+ 15. Kh1 Ng6 16. Qh5 fxe4 17. Rh3 f5 (17... h6 18. Bxh6 Bxh6 19. Qxh6 Qg7 { would be a better way to defend. }) 18. Qxh7+ Kf7 19. Rh6 { [%csl Gg6,Gf6][%cal Gh6f6] } 19... Ne7 20. Rf6+ Qxf6 21. Bxf6 Kxf6 22. Rf1 Rh8 23. Nxe4+ Kf7 24. Rxf5+ Nxf5 25. Qxf5+ { 1-0 White wins. } 1-0


