{ - Queen Sacrifice
- Piece Sacrifice
- Checkmate
- Kingside Attack
- Pawn Promotion
- Ideal Center
- Space Advantage
- Bishop Pair

May 2024 Game Of The Month had it all, a real thriller! Enjoy! }
1. e4 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 1... e6 { Black chooses the French apparently... } { [%clk 0:03:00] } 2. d4 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 2... b6 { ...but with a slight twist Black opted for the Owen Defence instead, a line generally starts with the moves 1.e4 b6 2.d4 Bb7. } { [%clk 0:03:01] } 3. Nf3 { [%clk 0:03:01] } 3... Bb7 { [%clk 0:03:03] } 4. Nc3 { [%clk 0:03:01] } (4. Bd3! { This avoids 4...Bb4 as in the game. } 4... Nf6 5. Qe2! { White is fighting for e4-square against black's d5-Ne4 idea. } 5... d5 6. e5 Ne4 7. Nbd2! { This is the whole point of delaying Nc3. White can meet } 7... Bb4 { with } 8. c3) 4... Bb4! { Similar to other modern chess openings Owen Defence aims to control the center with the pieces first. Black's main idea is to put pressure on the e4 and d4 squares playing d5 or c5. } { [%csl Re4][%cal Gb7e4,Rb4e1] [%clk 0:03:04] } 5. Bd3 { [%clk 0:02:59] } 5... Nf6 { The fight for the e4-square continues. White has few options to defend the e4-pawn. } { [%cal Gf6e4,Gb7e4] [%clk 0:03:05] } 6. Nd2! { I was suprised to discover that this move is the best option (by a small margin though) according to our friend Stockfish which not only protects e4-pawn and unpins the Nc3, but also opens up the d1-h5 diagonal for the queen.
Why is this move is so strong? Let's consider the alternatives: } { [%clk 0:02:40] } (6. Qe2 { The most popular move by far according Masters and Lichess Databases. } 6... d5! 7. e5 Ne4! { Play on the light squares with d5-Ae4 is one of the main ideas of Owen Defence we'll see time and again! } { [%csl Gc3][%cal Ge4c3,Gb4c3] } 8. Bxe4?? dxe4 $19 { [%cal Gd8d4] }) (6. Bg5 h6! { White has to part with the dark squared bishop to protect e4-pawn. }) (6. e5 Ne4! { and according to the Masters Database white might be better off sacrificing a pawn with } 7. O-O!?) 6... Bxc3?! { Black decided to give up their bishop unprovoked. Black is ill-advised to play like this as they need to play energetically to destroy or weaken white's center. You can find Grandmaster examples showing typical methods of fighting for the center in the next chapters. } { [%clk 0:02:33] } (6... d5 { Black might have played in the spirit of Owen Defence, then we might understand the ideas behind 6.Nd2! } 7. e5 Ne4 { the main idea of Owen Defence! } 8. Qg4! { [%cal Gg4g7,Gg4e4] } 8... Qg5 (8... Kf8 { Masters' choice. }) 9. Qxg5 Nxg5 10. Nb5 Kd7 11. a3 Be7 12. h4 Ne4 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Be2 Nc6 15. Be3 { White enjoys more space and better structure. } { Sveshnik - IJsbeer23, 1/2-1/2, -, https://lichess.org/Glt4WzeL }) (6... c5 { Nepomniachtchi's choice! Since d4-pawn lacks protection black starts attacking it. } { [%csl Gd4] } 7. a3 cxd4 8. axb4 dxc3 9. bxc3 Qc7 { [%csl Gc3][%cal Gc7c3] } 10. c4 d6 11. O-O Nbd7 12. Bb2 O-O 13. Qe2 a5! $132 { Ding Liren - Nepomniachtchi, I., 1/2-1/2, chess.com Speed 2019, https://lichess.org/UZ3dQnlr }) 7. bxc3 { Now White's center becomes even stronger and white has the bishop pair as well! } { [%csl Gd4,Gc3,Ge4] [%clk 0:02:42] } 7... c5 { [%clk 0:02:19] } (7... d5 { The main idea can still be applied though with lesser effect compared to previous move. } 8. e5 Ne4 9. Nb1! { Very instructive! Since the side has more space should avoid exchanges. White will castle and play f3 to kick the knight. }) 8. Ba3 { [%csl Gc5][%cal Gd4c5,Ga3c5] [%clk 0:02:35] } (8. e5 { with the idea of playing Ne4-Nd6, Bg5 was also logical underlining the absence of Black's dark-squared bishop. } { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gd2e4] } 8... Nd5 9. Ne4 { [%cal Gc1g5,Ge4d6] }) 8... O-O { [%clk 0:02:06] } (8... d5 9. e5 Ne4 { was still possible to have some play. }) 9. O-O { [%clk 0:02:35] } (9. dxc5 { This pawn could be taken as well but white decided to keep their mighty center no matter what. }) 9... Re8 { [%clk 0:02:06] } 10. Kh1 { [%clk 0:02:24] } (10. e5 { was possibile with the similar ideas mentioned above; intending Ne4-Bg5. } { [%cal Gd2e4] }) 10... d6 { Black keeps the bishop on a3 firmly blocked for the moment but this gives White free hand in the center. } { [%csl Ga3] [%clk 0:02:04] } (10... d5 { would still be a better way to continue. }) 11. f4! { White takes the opportunity and start playing aggressively on the kingside, preparing e4-e5. Keep a close eye on this pawn's career from now on! } { [%cal Ge4e5] [%clk 0:02:18] } (11. e5 { is now less effective due to tactics. } 11... dxe5 12. dxe5 Qd5! { [%cal Gd5g2,Gd5e5] } 13. Nf3 { [%csl Ge5] } 13... c4! $132) 11... d5 { It is not consistent with the previous move as Black could have played this earlier. } { [%clk 0:01:47] } 12. e5 { [%clk 0:01:57] } 12... Nfd7? { Only this is the real mistake! Black cannot fight for the center and strive for counterplay this way. Black's biggest mistake was maybe underestimating White's attack. } { [%clk 0:01:44] } (12... Ne4! { was still the only way to block White's light-squared bishop's diagonal and continue with ...f5. Black might have had some chances for counterplay. } { [%csl Gc3][%cal Gf7f5,Ge4c3] } 13. Bxe4 { If white tries to win a pawn black would be better, to illustrate the point; } 13... dxe4 14. dxc5? Qd7 $44 { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gd7a4] }) 13. Qg4 { Now White has everything under control with nice space advange, bishop pair and better development. } { [%clk 0:01:36] } 13... Qc7 { "Never a mate with Nf8", as the saying goes, } { [%clk 0:01:08] } (13... Nf8 { or }) (13... Ba6 { would be better. }) 14. f5! { Opening up more lines against the Black's king! } { [%clk 0:01:30] } (14. Bxh7+ { even this works now. } 14... Kxh7 15. f5!) 14... cxd4 { [%clk 0:01:06] } (14... exf5 15. Rxf5 Nf8 { would be more tenacious. Black might try to exchange pieces with ...Ba6 next. } { [%csl Rg4][%cal Gb7a6,Gb7c8,Rc8g4,Ra6d3] }) 15. f6! { [%clk 0:00:27] } 15... g6 { Now White can continue the attack in many ways but... } { [%clk 0:00:35] } 16. Bxg6! { First shot! } { [%clk 0:00:19] } 16... hxg6 { [%clk 0:00:14] } 17. Qxg6+!! { How often do we have the opportunity to sacrifice a piece and a queen? } { [%clk 0:00:19] } 17... fxg6 { [%clk 0:00:14] } 18. f7+ { White sacrificed a queen and a bishop for the f-pawn's advance! It's about to make history. } { [%clk 0:00:21] } 18... Kg7 { [%clk 0:00:15] } 19. fxe8=Q { White is still a piece down but black king is even more exposed and black's pieces are far from the action. } { [%clk 0:00:21] } 19... Nc6 { [%cal Ga8e8] [%clk 0:00:13] } 20. Qf7+ { [%clk 0:00:19] } 20... Kh6 { [%clk 0:00:13] } (20... Kh8 21. Rf3 { [%cal Gf3h3] }) 21. Rf3! { [%cal Gf3h3] [%clk 0:00:13] } 21... Ncxe5 { [%clk 0:00:14] } 22. Rh3+ { [%clk 0:00:13] } 22... Kg5 { [%clk 0:00:15] } 23. Nf3+! { [%clk 0:00:07] } 23... Nxf3 { [%clk 0:00:15] } 24. Bc1+ { [%clk 0:00:06] } (24. gxf3 { also mates. } { [%cal Ga1g1] }) 24... Kg4 { [%clk 0:00:13] } 25. Qxg6+ { [%clk 0:00:03] } (25. Qxf3#) 25... Ng5 { [%clk 0:00:12] } 26. Qxg5# { An exciting and instructive attacking game by Javier1009! } { [%clk 0:00:03] } 1-0


