{ 2024 September Game of The Month featuring a very high level bullet clash! In this very exciting game both kings are castled on the opposite sides, and as always, the side who is faster at attacking the opponent's king won!

It's my first time annotating a bullet game, i hope you enjoy this exciting battle! }
1. Nf3 { [%clk 0:01:00] } (1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. h4 { The usual way to avoid the Grünfeld with an early h4. } 3... c5 4. d5 Bg7 5. Nc3 d6 6. e4 { White keeps the knight on g1-square flexible in this case. } { [%cal Rg1e2,Rg1f3] }) 1... Nf6 { [%clk 0:01:00] } 2. d4 { [%clk 0:01:00] } 2... g6 { [%clk 0:01:00] } 3. c4 { [%clk 0:01:00] } 3... Bg7 { [%clk 0:01:00] } 4. h4 { I'm not sure if this move was played to avoid the Grünfeld. As noted above on the first move, modern practice witnesses a slightly different move order to avoid the Grünfeld Defence.
As far as i know, IM MassterofMayhem playing with the black pieces usually prefers the King's Indian Defence rather than Grünfeld. } { [%clk 0:00:59] } 4... d6 { Starting immeadiate counterplay in the center with } { [%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] [%clk 0:01:00] } (4... c5! { and going for Benoni type of position is usually preffered against early h4 moves, since early h4 is not considered problematic against Benoni. }) 5. h5 { An early sacrifice to open up the h-file, may not be objectively the best but a good strategy for a bullet game! } { [%clk 0:00:59] } 5... Nxh5 { [%clk 0:00:58] } 6. Nc3 { [%clk 0:00:59] } 6... Nf6 { [%cal Gc1h6] [%clk 0:00:58] } 7. Bh6 { This is the point of the 5th move. White wants to attack on the dark squares and h-file from the very beggining. } { [%clk 0:00:58] } 7... Bxh6 { [%clk 0:00:56] } 8. Rxh6 { [%clk 0:00:58] } 8... c5 { Black can go for ...e5 or ...c5 pushes. He chose the latter to open up the d8-a5 diagonal. It makes perfect sense to start counterplay in the center and on the queenside. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Rd8a5,Gc5d4] [%clk 0:00:56] } 9. Qd2 { White's idea is to fully mobilize their forces as soon as possible and prepare for the attack. } { [%cal Ge1c1] [%clk 0:00:58] } 9... cxd4 { [%clk 0:00:56] } 10. Nxd4 { [%clk 0:00:58] } 10... Nc6 { [%clk 0:00:55] } 11. O-O-O { [%clk 0:00:57] } 11... Nxd4 { Black welcomes the exchanges as he's up a pawn. } { [%clk 0:00:52] } 12. Qxd4 { [%clk 0:00:56] } 12... O-O! { Castling right into the fire! Even though black will be mated in the end, black's king is perfectly safe here. Even more solid way to keep in mind such positions is } { [%clk 0:00:52] } (12... Kf8! { [%cal Rf8g7] } 13. Ne4 Kg7 { The rook would be better placed on h8 to play ...h5 if necessary. A sample line, } { [%csl Rh8] } 14. Rh4 h5 15. Nxf6 exf6 16. Qxd6 Qa5 { Black would take over the initiative by giving back the pawn to create counterplay as white's king starts feeling the tension. } { [%csl Rc1,Ga2][%cal Gc8f5,Ga8d8] }) 13. f3 { [%cal Ge2e4,Gg2g4] [%clk 0:00:55] } 13... Be6 { [%csl Gc4][%cal Ga8c8] [%clk 0:00:51] } 14. e4 { [%cal Gf1e2,Gd1h1] [%clk 0:00:54] } 14... Rc8 { [%clk 0:00:50] } 15. Be2 { We're slowly approaching the crucial phase of the game. White is about to play Rdh1 and crush through by bringing their queen into the action. Can Black create enough play on the queenside? } { [%cal Gd1h1] [%clk 0:00:53] } (15. Qxa7 Bxc4 { was black's idea. }) 15... a6 { A typical idea but Stockfish considers it to be rather slow. Instead suggesting to activate and bring the queen closer to the kingside and exchange if necessary. } { [%cal Gb7b5] [%clk 0:00:49] } (15... Qa5! { [%csl Re5,Gg5][%cal Ga5e5,Ge5g5] } 16. Rdh1 Qg5+ 17. Kb1 Nh5! { One of Stockfish's resources. } { [%csl Rh6] }) (15... Qb6! { The point is c4-pawn would be hanging if white avoids this exchange. } { [%csl Gc4,Gd4] } 16. Qd2 (16. Qxb6 axb6 { White should have practical companstation for the missing pawn in a bullet game but Stockfish considers this position as winning since } { [%csl Gc4] } 17. b3 Nh5! $19 { wins an exchange. } { [%csl Gh6][%cal Gg8g7] }) 16... Bxc4 $19 17. Rdh1 { Black can defend against white's attack and has a winning position I'll leave it to the reader to find possible defences against white's Rxh7. Of course black should not play, } { [%csl Gh7][%cal Gh6h7] } 17... Bxe2? 18. Rxh7! $18 { [%cal Gd2h6] }) 16. Rdh1 { Now white will prepare deadly threats including the sacrifice on h7! } { [%csl Gh6][%cal Gd4d2,Gd4e3,Gd2h6,Rh6h7] [%clk 0:00:53] } 16... b5? { Combination alert! Even though black was preparing this idea, it's a big mistake! } { [%clk 0:00:49] } 17. cxb5? { [%clk 0:00:52] } (17. Qe3!! { Which would win on the spot as Rxh7 can not be averted! } { [%cal Gh6h7] } 17... Rc5 { only defence! } { [%cal Gc5h5] } (17... Qd7 18. Rxh7 { [%cal Ge3h6] }) 18. Nd5!! { closing the fifth rank! } 18... Bxd5 19. Rxh7!! { white mates! } { [%cal Ge3h6,Gh7g7] }) 17... axb5 { [%clk 0:00:48] } 18. Kb1 { [%clk 0:00:51] } 18... Qa5 { Rxc3 is a threat! } { [%csl Rc3][%cal Rc8c3,Ba5a2] [%clk 0:00:47] } 19. a3 { Meeting black's threats before starting an action on the black's king. } { [%clk 0:00:40] } 19... Bc4? { This logical move is a mistake but the reason is not easy to realize in a bullet game! } { [%clk 0:00:40] } (19... Rc5! { a deep multipurpose move! Black rooks will attack over the c-file and cover the black's king via fifth rank! The tactical point is } { [%cal Rc5h5,Rf8c8] } 20. b4? Qxa3 21. bxc5 b4 $19 { Black's attack would be faster! }) 20. Bxc4 { [%clk 0:00:38] } 20... Rxc4 { [%clk 0:00:39] } 21. Qxf6!! { White removes the best defender of the black's king, but can white get more than a draw with the rooks on the h-file? } { [%clk 0:00:29] } 21... exf6 { [%clk 0:00:27] } 22. Rxh7 { [%clk 0:00:28] } 22... g5 $7 { [%cal Gg8g7,Gg7g6] [%clk 0:00:21] } 23. Nd5! { [%csl Gf6,Ge7][%cal Gd5e7,Gd5f6] [%clk 0:00:20] } 23... Qd8 { Black offers draw } { [%clk 0:00:17] } 24. Ne3!! { Amazing retreat with a deadly threat! } { [%cal Ge3f5] [%clk 0:00:12] } 24... Rc5? { [%clk 0:00:16] } (24... Qc8! { An ingenious way to survive according to Stockfish. } { [%csl Ge3] } 25. Nf5 (25. R7h6 Rd8 26. Nf5 Qxf5 { This is the second point of black's defence. } 27. exf5 { [%cal Rh6f6] } 27... Kg7 { with a better structure white is better in the rook endgame but it's very far from over. } { [%csl Rf6][%cal Gg7f6] }) 25... Rc1+! { is the first point of 24...Qc8. } 26. Rxc1 Qxc1+ 27. Kxc1 Kxh7 $13) 25. Nf5 { Here black lost on time, but black's king can not be saved anyway. } { [%clk 0:00:09] } 25... Rxf5 26. exf5 { with g6-square is covered it's perfect mating net.
An imaginative attacking game by dauANHbac. } { [%csl Rg8] } 1-0


